{ In the first lecture, we will check the most typical endgames in Philidor Defence. You will find 16 commented examples 2-17 } 1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. dxe5 dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 { The most common endgame in this variation arises only after five moves. White often tries this not very ambitious approach to simplify the position and make a draw. However, things are far from simple. Still, too many pieces are on the board, and in the following games, you will see how Black should fight and play for a win. The most critical line is } 6. Bc4 { here I suggest } 6... Be6 7. Bxe6 fxe6 { The double pawns are very useful here, controlling important central squares and giving Black counterplay on the semi-open "f" and "d" files } *
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Typical Endgames, Open d-file"]
[Black "Model Games for Black"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "GM Dejan Bojkov"]
[PlyCount "0"]

{The following three examples are model games for Black how to handle the typical endgame with the open d-file}  *

[Event "1st GM"]
[Site "Kish IRI"]
[Date "2023.11.17"]
[Round "10"]
[White "Ardeshi, M..."]
[Black "Bojkov, D..."]
[Result "0-1"]
[ECO "C41"]
[WhiteElo "2339"]
[BlackElo "2398"]
[Annotator "GM Dejan Bojkov"]
[PlyCount "70"]
[EventDate "2023.??.??"]

1. e4 {This game is an illustration of what might go wrong in the Philidor if White plays obvious, natural moves but without a clear plan.} d6 (1... e5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4) 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 {[%cal Gd4e5,Gd6e5]} 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. Bc4 Be7 6. O-O O-O {[%csl Gb6][%cal Gd7b6]} 7. Re1 c6 8. a4 {[%cal Gd7b6]} a5 9. b3 h6 10. Ba3 {[%cal Gc1b2,Gb2a3]} Re8 {[%cal Gh7h6,Gf8e8]} 11. h3 Nh7 {[%csl Rf3,Be7,Bc8,Ye5,Yd6][%cal Gh7g5,Re7g5,Re7f6,Yd7d6,Ye7e5]} 12. dxe5 $6 {Fxing the center is a concession. Normally, the pressure should favor White and he should try to gain something out of it.} dxe5 13. Bxe7 {The continuation of the wrong idea. This trade is also favourable for Black.} Qxe7 $10 14. Qd2 Nc5 {[%csl Yc3,Yf3,Yd5,Yf5,Rf4,Rd4][%cal Yf3h4,Yh4f5,Yc3d5,Yc6d5]} 15. Rad1 Ng5 16. Nxg5 hxg5 17. Qd6 $6 {The endgame is superior for Black. It is easier to defend along the d-file, and the king can be centralized.} Kf8 18. Qxe7+ Kxe7 $15 {A success story for the second player. He traded a pair of light pieces and had better control over the central squares. The d-file has little to no importance as there are no infiltration points in the black camp.} 19. Rd2 Be6 20. Bxe6 Nxe6 21. Ne2 ({The best defense was discovered by the machine} 21. Nd1 $1 Red8 22. Rxd8 Rxd8 23. Ne3 $1 {when the infiltration} Rd2 24. Rc1 {[%csl Ra5,Rb7,Rc4][%cal Bg1f1,Bf1e1,Be3c4] yiled nothing to Black.}) 21... Rad8 (21... Red8 $1 {was definitely more natural} 22. Red1 Rxd2 23. Rxd2 b5) 22. Red1 Rxd2 23. Rxd2 b5 ({Keeping the second pair of rooks is better.} 23... Rd8 24. Rxd8 Kxd8 25. Kf1 Kc7 {[%cal Gc7b6,Gb6c5,Gc5b4,Gb4a3]} 26. Ke1 b5 {[%csl Re4,Ra4][%cal Re6c5,Rc5e4,Rc5a4,Gc7b6,Gb6c5]} 27. Kd2 Kb6 $15 {minimizes Black's edge.}) 24. Nc3 Nd4 25. f3 Rb8 $1 {The black rook is more valuable than its counterpart.} 26. Kf2 Kd6 $1 27. Ne2 Kc5 28. axb5 ({Or} 28. Nxd4 exd4 29. axb5 cxb5 {[%cal Gb8a8,Ga5a1]}) 28... cxb5 {[%csl Gd4,Gb8,Gc5,Ga4][%cal Ga5a4] All the black pieces are superior and the creation of an outside passer is inevitable.} 29. Nc1 Kb4 $1 30. Ke3 Kc3 31. Na2+ Kb2 32. c3+ Nc2+ 33. Kd3 Rd8+ 34. Ke2 Rxd2+ 35. Kxd2 Na1 {0-1 Black wins} 0-1

