1. e4 {We are going to check the typical endgames as the move order that I suggest involves an invitation into one. Queenside Attack.} d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. dxe5 dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 6. Nf3 {There are many ways to reach the main endgame position.} ({Another straightforward plan is} 6. Bg5 Be6 7. O-O-O+ {It should be said in advance, that the castling does not seem to bother the second player at all.} Nbd7 8. Nd5 $6 Kc8 9. f3 c6 10. c4 (10. Nc3 b5 11. a3 (11. Kb1 Bc5 12. Nge2 b4 $6 (12... a5) (12... Ne8 $17) 13. Na4 Be7 14. Nc1 (14. Be3 $1) 14... Nb6 $1 15. Nxb6+ axb6 16. Bd2 Kc7 17. c3 bxc3 18. Bxc3 Nd7 $15 19. Bd3 f6 20. Rd2 Nc5 21. b3 b5 $15 22. Rhd1 Rhb8 (22... Rhd8) 23. Bf1 Nd7 24. Rc2 c5 25. Bb4 $1 Kb6 26. Be1 Ra3 27. Bf2 Rba8 28. b4 Kc6 29. bxc5 R8a4 30. Rd3 Rb4+ 31. Rb2 Raa4 32. a3 (32. Nb3 $1 Nxc5 33. Rc3 Bc4 34. Rc1 $13) 32... Rxb2+ 33. Kxb2 Bc4 34. Rd1 Nxc5 35. Bxc4 bxc4 36. Kc3 Rxa3+ 37. Kxc4 Na4 {0-1 (37) Kosmadakis,D (1912) -Bojkov, D (2521) Heraklion GRE 2009} 38. Ne2 Nb2#) 11... b4 (11... h6 $17 12. Be3 (12. Bh4 a5) 12... Kc7) (11... a5 $17) 12. Ba6+ $6 (12. axb4 Bxb4 13. Nge2) 12... Kc7 {[%csl Ra6]} 13. axb4 Bxb4 14. Nge2 Nc5 15. Bd3 a5 16. Kb1 Rhb8 17. Ka1 a4 18. Na2 Ba5 19. Bxf6 gxf6 20. f4 Nxd3 21. cxd3 Bg4 22. Nac1 a3 23. b3 Bxe2 24. Nxe2 Rxb3 25. fxe5 Rb2 26. Nc1 Bc3 27. Na2 Bd4 28. Rc1 Rb3+ {0-1 (28) Iliev,D (2153) -Bojkov,D (2453) Slanchev Briag 2004}) 10... Bc5 11. Nc3 h6 12. Bh4 Nb6 13. b3 Ba3+ 14. Kc2 a5 15. Nge2 a4 16. Nc1 Bc5 17. Nd3 Bd4 18. Be2 axb3+ 19. axb3 Ra3 20. Nb2 Kc7 21. g4 Rha8 22. Bg3 Kc8 23. Rhf1 Nfd7 24. Bf2 Bxf2 25. Rxf2 Nc5 26. Nd3 Nxd3 27. Rxd3 Nd7 28. Nb1 Ra1 29. Rd2 Nc5 30. Bf1 Nxb3 31. Kxb3 Rxb1+ 32. Rb2 Re1 33. Kc3 Kc7 34. Bd3 Raa1 35. Rfc2 Re3 36. Ra2 Rxa2 37. Rxa2 b5 {0-1 (37) Angelov,A (2220) -Bojkov,D (2394) Slanchev Briag 2003}) ({White's most common reaction is} 6. Bc4 Be6 7. Bxe6 fxe6 {[%csl Gg5] Are the doubled pawns weak or good? The answer seems obvious- they are isolated and might be attacked. Still, a few points make their existence fun for the second player. First, they covered a lot of central squares, thus making the black king's position safer. The king would prefer to stay in the middle, too. Second- stability means that they might face a strong attack whenever White castles, regardless of the flank.} 8. Bg5 (8. Be3 {[%csl Ge3]} Bd6 (8... Bb4 $1) 9. f3 (9. Nge2 Nc6 10. h3 Ke7 11. O-O-O a6 12. f3 b5 13. Rhg1 Rhb8 14. g3 a5 (14... Na5 $1) 15. Rd2 (15. a4 $1 bxa4 16. Nxa4 Rb4 17. b3) 15... a4 16. Nd1 Na5 17. Bf2 Nc4 18. Rd3 Nd7 19. Ne3 Na5 20. Rdd1 Rf8 21. f4 Nc5 22. Nc3 (22. Nf5+ exf5 23. fxe5 Nxe4 24. exd6+ cxd6) 22... b4 23. Ncd5+ exd5 24. Nxd5+ Kd7 25. fxe5 Rxf2 26. exd6 b3 27. cxb3 axb3 28. a3 Nc4 29. dxc7 Rc2+ 30. Kb1 Rxb2+ {0-1 (30) Santiago Dominguez (1952) -Bojkov,D (2498) Ferrol 2008}) 9... Ke7 10. Nh3 Nc6 11. O-O-O a6 12. Nf2 b5 13. Nd3 Nd7 {[%csl Rc5]} 14. Rhf1 h6 15. Nb1 (15. h4) 15... Na5 16. b3 c5 17. Rd2 c4 18. Nf2 Rhc8 19. Kb2 b4 20. c3 bxc3+ 21. Nxc3 cxb3 22. axb3 Rab8 {0-1 (22) Kottwitz,D (2041) -Bojkov,D (2516) Jena 2005}) ({Let's assume that White would like to castle short instead} 8. Nge2 Bd6 9. O-O Ke7 10. Be3 Nc6 11. f3 {Then there will be no major difference in Black's approach as he would continue} Rag8 {[%cal Gg7g5,Gh7h5,Gg5g4,Yf6h5,Yh5f4] with similar attacking ideas, but on the opposite side of the board!}) 8... Bd6 9. O-O-O {Whenever White castles, the plan remains the same- finish the development, place the king in the middle, bring the kingside rook to the b8- square and start pushing the pawns.} Ke7 10. Nge2 Nc6 11. f3 a6 12. Be3 b5 13. g4 Rhb8 {[%csl Ga5,Ga8,Gb4,Gb8,Rc1,Ge7][%cal Gb5b4,Ga6a5,Rc6a5,Ra5c4]} 14. Ng3 a5 15. Nce2 a4 $15 {[%csl Ba4][%cal Bb5b4,Yc3a4]} 16. Rdf1 Na5 17. g5 Nd7 18. f4 Nc4 $1 19. Bd2 (19. Bg1 b4 20. f5 b3 $40 21. cxb3 axb3 22. a3 {[%csl Ga3,Gb8,Ga8][%cal Gc4b2,Gd6a3]}) 19... Nxd2 (19... b4) 20. Kxd2 {[%csl Re6][%cal Gf4f5,Gf5e6,Rg3f5,Re2c3,Rc3d5]} exf4 21. Nxf4 Ne5 22. Nge2 Rf8 (22... Nc4+ 23. Kc1 Bc5 $19 {[%csl Rd2][%cal Bc5e3,Rc4d2,Rb8d8]}) 23. h4 b4 24. Rh3 Nc4+ 25. Kc1 Be5 26. c3 bxc3 27. bxc3 Rab8 28. g6 h6 29. Rhf3 Na3 30. Kd2 Rb2+ 31. Kd3 Rd8+ 32. Nd4 c5 33. Nfxe6 c4+ 34. Ke3 Nc2+ 35. Nxc2 Rd3+ {0-1 (35) Pousada Garcia,D (1892) -Bojkov,D (2445) Ferrol 2006}) (6. Bd2 Bc5 7. O-O-O Ke7 8. f3 c6 9. Bc4 b5 10. Bb3 Nbd7 11. Bg5 h6 12. Bh4 a5 13. a4 b4 14. Nb1 Be3+ 15. Nd2 Nc5 16. Bg3 Rd8 $1 17. Bxe5 Ra7 18. Ne2 Nxb3+ 19. cxb3 Rad7 20. Bf4 Rxd2 {0-1 (20) Krasucki,Y (1899) -Bojkov,D (2505) Fourmies 2005}) 6... Bd6 7. Bg5 Be6 8. O-O-O Nbd7 9. Bb5 Kc8 10. Bxd7+ Nxd7 11. a3 Bc5 12. Rd2 f6 13. Be3 Bxe3 14. fxe3 {[%csl Gc6][%cal Gd6d7,Gc5c6]} c6 $17 {[%csl Bd4,Bd5,Bf5,Bf4][%cal Be5f4,Be5d4,Bc6d5,Be6f5,Be6d5]} 15. Nh4 g6 16. h3 Kc7 17. Rf1 Rhf8 18. b3 Kd8 19. g4 Ke7 20. Rdf2 b5 21. Kb2 a5 22. Nf3 Nc5 {[%csl Re4][%cal Rc5e4,Rb5b4]} 23. Nd2 Rfd8 24. Ncb1 Nd7 25. Nc3 Nb6 26. Nf3 Rf8 27. Ne1 b4 {[%cal Rc3a4]} 28. axb4 axb4 29. Na2 c5 {[%csl Bf6,Be5,Bc5,Bb4][%cal Be6h3,Be6a2]} 30. Nd3 Nd7 31. Ra1 Rh8 32. Rg1 g5 {[%csl Rg4,Rh3,Re4,Rb3,Rc2][%cal Gh7h5]} 33. h4 gxh4 34. g5 Rag8 35. gxf6+ Nxf6 36. Rgf1 Nxe4 37. Rh2 h3 38. Nxe5 Rg2 39. Rfh1 Nf2 40. Rxg2 hxg2 41. Rg1 Rg8 {0-1 Black wins.} 0-1

