{The following two examples of how Black should handle the endgames with opposite-colored bishops}  *

[Event "Santa Cruz de la Palma op"]
[Site "Santa Cruz de Tenerife"]
[Date "2023.11.17"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Fernandez Garcia, Jose Luis"]
[Black "Franco Ocampos, Zenon"]
[Result "0-1"]
[WhiteElo "2445"]
[BlackElo "2490"]
[Annotator "GM Dejan Bojkov"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "r6r/ppkn3p/2p1pp2/4p3/4P3/4bP2/PPP1N1PP/1K1R1B1R b - - 0 16"]
[PlyCount "69"]
[EventDate "2023.??.??"]

{[#] OCB Endgame. Black-dark-squared bishop, is usually favorable for the second player. As in most pawn structures with statical elements, the presence of opposite-colored bishops is often an important factor that favors the player with the more active bishop.} 16... h5 {[%csl Ge5,Ge6,Gf6,Rg2][%cal Ge6f5,Ge6d5,Ge5d4,Ge5f4,Ga8g8,Gg8g2,Gh7h5,Gh5h4]} 17. g3 a5 18. Bh3 Nc5 19. Nc1 h4 20. Nd3 Nxd3 21. Rxd3 hxg3 22. hxg3 Bf2 ({Stronger was} 22... Rag8 $1 23. Rxe3 (23. g4 Bg5 $17 {[%csl Rh3]}) (23. Rdd1 $1 Rxg3 24. Bxe6 Rxh1 25. Rxh1 Rxf3 {with a chance to survive, although White still needs to suffer a lot.}) 23... Rxg3 $19) 23. Rdd1 Rae8 24. Bg4 Rxh1 25. Rxh1 Kd6 26. Bh5 Rh8 27. g4 b5 28. c3 c5 29. Kc2 c4 30. Rd1+ Ke7 31. a4 $2 (31. a3 $5) (31. b3 $1) 31... b4 32. cxb4 axb4 33. b3 c3 $17 {[%csl Gc3]} 34. a5 f5 35. exf5 exf5 36. Rd5 Bd4 {Once the black rook finds an open file it would be all over.} 37. f4 (37. Rb5 fxg4 38. fxg4 Rf8 39. Bg6 Rf2+ 40. Kd1 Rd2+ 41. Kc1 Rg2 42. Bf5 Be3+ 43. Kd1 Kf6 $19) 37... fxg4 38. fxe5 Rxh5 39. Rxd4 Rh2+ 40. Kc1 g3 41. Rxb4 g2 42. Rg4 Rh1+ 43. Kc2 {g1} g1=Q 44. Rxg1 Rxg1 45. Kxc3 Rg4 46. b4 Kd7 47. b5 Ra4 48. a6 Kc7 49. Kd3 Kb6 50. e6 Rh4 {0-1 Black wins.} 0-1

