{[#] Another OCB example.} 16. Nd1 Nd7 17. Ne3 b5 18. h4 Nf6 19. h5 Rad8 20. Rh4 Nd7 21. Ng4 Nf6 (21... c5 $5) 22. Rd1 $6 Nxg4 $5 {Black is not afraid of a pure opposite-colored endgame but with rooks on the board.} 23. Rxg4 Kf6 24. c3 Bc5 25. Kc2 Rxd1 26. Kxd1 Rd8+ {[%csl Rg4][%cal Gc5e3,Gd8d2] As the White rook is a passive observer on the kingside, Black wants to infiltrate through the center.} 27. Kc2 Bf2 $1 {[%csl Gg6][%cal Gg7g6,Gh5g6,Gh7h5]} 28. f4 Be3 29. fxe5+ Kxe5 $1 {[%csl Re5] Remember, any black piece can capitalize on the weakness of the e5-outpost.} 30. Bd3 (30. Rxg7 $4 Rd2+) 30... Rd7 ({Worse was} 30... c5 31. b3 Bh6 32. Rg3 Rf8 33. Rf3 Rxf3 34. gxf3 Kf4 35. a4 $1 {and Wite forces reliefing trades.}) 31. Rg3 Bf4 32. Rf3 c5 33. g3 Bg5 34. b3 Bf6 35. Rf4 Rd6 36. Rg4 h6 37. a3 $2 ({Most likely White should not survive the dark-squared infiltration after} 37. Rf4 b4 {[%cal Bd4e3,Be5d4] neither, but this was at least more resilient.}) 37... Bg5 38. c4 b4 39. axb4 cxb4 {[%csl Rg4][%cal Be5d4,Bd4e3,Be3f3,Yf3g4]} 40. c5 Rc6 41. Bc4 Rxc5 {0-1 Black wins.} 0-1

