{ In the following six examples, we will see and endgame structure which is very common in Philidor Defence - the structure with double e-pawns. It usually arises after the following moves. } 1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. dxe5 dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 6. Bc4 Be6 7. Bxe6 fxe6 { Black's pawns can't be attacked easily. They also control important squares in the centre and give decent black counterplay. } *
[Event "Winterthur"]
[Site "Winterthur"]
[Date "2023.11.17"]
[Round "1"]
[White "Baumann, K....."]
[Black "Bojkov, D....."]
[Result "0-1"]
[ECO "B00"]
[WhiteElo "1895"]
[BlackElo "2516"]
[Annotator "GM Dejan Bojkov"]
[PlyCount "76"]
[EventDate "2023.??.??"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. dxe5 dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 {In the endgame, White is often looking for a way to trade the Bd6, but this only strengthens the pawn chain of the second player.} 6. Bc4 (6. Nf3 Bd6 7. Bg5 Be6 8. Nb5 {[%cal Gb5d6] is another way to swap the bishop. Then} Ke7 9. Nxd6 cxd6 10. O-O-O Nbd7 {[%csl Gf6][%cal Gd7f6,Gh7h6,Gg5f6,Gg7f6]} 11. Bb5 Nc5 12. Rhe1 a6 (12... Rhd8 $5 {[%csl Bf6][%cal Gd8d6,Gh7h6,Bh4e7,Bf6e4,Bc5e4] looks more accurate, overprotecting the d6-point, thus enabling the recapture on f6 with a king.} 13. Nd2 Rac8) 13. Bf1 Rhc8 14. Kb1 {[%csl Rf6,Rd6][%cal Gh4e7]} b5 (14... Rc6 $5 15. Nd2 h6 {[%csl Gh6][%cal Gh7h6]} 16. Bh4 g5 {[%csl Rh6,Rg5,Re5,Rd6][%cal Ge6h3,Ge6a2]} 17. Bg3 Nfd7 $15) 15. Nd2 (15. Bxf6+ $5 gxf6 16. Nh4 {[%csl Ga6,Gb1][%cal Ga6a5,Gb5b4,Ga5a4]}) 15... h6 $1 16. Bh4 (16. Bxf6+ Kxf6 $15 {[%cal Gd6d5,Gf7f5,Gg7g6,Ga6a5,Gb5b4]}) 16... g5 17. Bg3 Nh5 18. f3 Nxg3 19. hxg3 h5 $15 20. Be2 Rh8 21. Rh1 Rh6 (21... f5 $5 22. exf5 Bxf5 23. Nf1 Be6 24. Ne3 Rag8 $15) 22. Rh2 Rah8 23. Rdh1 Kf6 (23... h4 $1 24. gxh4 (24. Nf1 f5 25. exf5 Bxf5 26. Ne3 Be6 $17) 24... Rxh4 25. Rxh4 Rxh4 26. Rxh4 gxh4 $19 {[%cal Ge7f6,Gf6g5,Gg5f4,Gf4g3]}) (23... d5 $5 24. exd5 Bxd5) 24. Nf1 $1 h4 25. Ne3 Kg6 26. g4 Kf6 27. Rd1 Ke7 28. a3 Rb8 29. Rdh1 Rg6 30. b3 Rgg8 31. Rd1 Rgc8 32. Rhh1 Rc6 33. Kb2 Rbc8 34. Rc1 Rb8 35. Rcd1 Nd7 36. Rd3 Nb6 37. Kc1 Nd7 38. Kb2 Rbb6 39. Rhd1 Nc5 40. R3d2 a5 41. Bf1 Rc8 42. Be2 Rcb8 43. Bf1 Rc6 44. Be2 Nd7 45. Bf1 Nf8 46. Be2 Ng6 47. Bf1 Nf4 48. Rc1 b4 49. a4 $6 (49. Ra1 $13) (49. axb4 axb4 50. Ra1 $13) 49... Rc3 50. Re1 Rbc8 51. Bc4 Rc6 52. Rf2 Bxc4 53. Nxc4 {[%cal Gc6c5,Gc5a5]} R6xc4 $1 {Positional Exchange Sacrifice. A chance you need to look for when the statical balance favors you.} 54. bxc4 Ne6 55. Ra1 Nd4 {[%cal Ge7d7,Gd7c6,Gc6c5,Gc5c4]} ({Correct was} 55... Nc5 $1 {[%cal Rc5a4,Ra1d1,Rd1d3,Rd3c3] The knight is not as pretty here, but is working better!} 56. Rff1 Rxc4 57. Rf2 Rc3 58. Rff1 {[%csl Ra4,Rf1,Ra1][%cal Gf2f1,Gf1f2,Gc5a4]} (58. Rd2 h3 $1 59. gxh3 Rxf3 $19) 58... Kd7 59. Rf2 Kc6 60. Rff1 Nd7 (60... Re3 61. Rf2 Nd7) 61. Rf2 Nb6 62. Rff1 Nc4+) 56. Rd1 $1 Rxc4 57. Rd3 $1 {[%cal Gc2c3]} Ke6 58. Rfd2 f6 59. c3 bxc3+ 60. Rxc3 Rxa4 61. Ra3 Rb4+ 62. Ka2 a4 63. Rc3 d5 (63... Nb5 64. Re3 Rc4 $17) 64. Rb2 Rb3 65. Rbxb3 axb3+ 66. Kb2 Kd7 67. Rc5 dxe4 68. fxe4 Kd6 69. Ra5 Ke6 70. Ra6+ Kf7 71. Rb6 Kg6 72. Kb1 {1/2-1/2 (72) Faruk,K (2189) -Bojkov,D (2394) Istanbul 2003}) 6... Be6 7. Bxe6 fxe6 8. Bg5 (8. Nf3 Nc6 9. O-O a6 10. Ng5 Kd7 11. Rd1+ Bd6 12. Nf7 Rhf8 13. Nxd6 cxd6 14. Be3 Ke7 15. Rd2 b5 16. f3 Rfc8 17. a4 b4 18. Na2 Rab8 19. Nc1 Nd4 20. Bxd4 exd4 21. Rxd4 Rxc2 22. Nd3 a5 23. Rc1 Rbc8 24. Rxc2 Rxc2 25. Nxb4 axb4 26. Rxb4 Nd7 27. Rb7 Kd8 28. b4 Rc7 29. Rb5 Ra7 30. a5 Kc7 31. f4 h6 {0-1 (31) Di Paolo R (2312) Georgiev,V (2584) Genova 2001}) 8... Bd6 9. O-O-O Ke7 10. Nb5 $6 Nc6 (10... h6 11. Bxf6+ gxf6 12. Nxd6 cxd6 $15) 11. Nxd6 (11. f3 $1 h6 12. Be3) 11... cxd6 {[%csl Ge5,Gd6,Ge6,Ge7] Now it is a favorable version of the Classical-Najdorf-Sveshnikov Sicilian type of endgame for Black. His king is safe and useful; the pawns on either side of the board might move forward, while the white pieces lack good diagonals (the bishop) and outposts - the knight.} 12. f3 {[%cal Gh7h6]} Rac8 (12... h6 $1 13. Bh4 (13. Bxf6+ gxf6 {[%csl Rg2][%cal Ga8g8,Gg8g2,Rh6h5,Rh5h4,Gb7b5,Ga7a5,Gf6f5,Gd6d5]}) 13... g5 14. Bf2 d5 $15) 13. Ne2 h6 14. Be3 a6 15. Rd2 Na5 (15... d5 16. exd5 exd5 17. Bf2) 16. b3 Rc6 17. Kb2 {[%csl Rb4][%cal Gb7b5]} b5 18. c3 (18. Nc1 $3 Nb7 19. Nd3 a5 20. g4 $14) 18... Rhc8 19. Rc2 d5 $1 20. exd5 exd5 21. Rhc1 g5 22. g4 (22. Ng3 Ke6 23. Re2 $13) 22... Nb7 23. Ng3 Nd6 24. h3 a5 25. Rh2 a4 26. h4 a3+ $1 27. Kxa3 $2 b4+ 28. Kb2 (28. Kxb4 Rb8+ 29. Ka3 Nc4+ 30. bxc4 Ra6#) 28... bxc3+ 29. Kc2 d4 30. hxg5 Nd5 $1 31. gxh6 Nxe3+ 32. Kd3 Nd5 33. Nf5+ Nxf5 34. gxf5 Nb4+ 35. Ke4 d3 36. Rg1 c2 37. h7 c1=Q 38. Rxc1 Rxc1 {0-1 Black wins.} 0-1

