1. d4 d6 2. e4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. dxe5 dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 6. Bc4 Be6 ( 6... Bb4 7. Bd2 Ke7 8. Nf3 Nbd7 9. O-O-O Bd6 10. Rhe1 Nb6 11. Bb3 a6 12. Ng5 Be6 $6 13. f4 $1 ) 7. Bxe6 fxe6 8. Be3 $1 { White's plan is better illustrated in this game by Walter Browne. } 8... Bd6 { Not the optimal move. } 9. f3 a6 10. Nge2 ( 10. O-O-O Ke7 ) 10... Nc6 ( 10... Nbd7 ) 11. Nd1 $14 { [%csl Gc3,Rd4,Rb4,Gd1,Ge5,Ge2][%cal Gd1f2,Gf2d3,Gc2c3,Ge1d2,Gd2c2,Ge3f2,Gf2g3,Gg3e5] The knights are aimed against the e5-pawn. [ Nf2-d3, Kd2, c3, Kc2] } ( 11. O-O-O ) 11... b5 { White's plan is venomous, but the second player has ways to counter it. } ( { One idea is } 11... Ke7 $5 12. Nf2 Nb4 13. Kd2 c5 { [%csl Gb5,Gc4,Rd3][%cal Gc7c5,Gc5c4,Gb7b5,Rc2c3,Gb4c6,Gc6d4] } 14. c3 Nc6 $13 { [%cal Gb7b5,Gc5c4] Depriving the white knights of their optimal squares, while fixing an outpost deep in the opponent's camp. Similar to the game Kosteniuk-Savina. } ) 12. Nf2 Nb4 ( 12... Na5 13. Nd3 Nc4 14. Bf2 $14 ) 13. Kd2 c5 $6 14. a4 $1 ( 14. a3 $6 Nc6 15. Nd3 Nd7 16. a4 $5 ) 14... Kc7 15. Nc3 ( 15. c3 $2 Nc6 16. Nd3 Na5 ) 15... Kc6 16. Ra3 $1 Nd7 17. Rha1 Nb6 18. b3 Bc7 ( 18... Rhd8 19. Kc1 c4 $2 ( 19... bxa4 $2 20. Nxa4 ) 20. Bxb6 Kxb6 21. axb5 $16 ) 19. axb5+ axb5 20. Ra7 Rxa7 21. Rxa7 Rd8+ 22. Kc1 Rd7 ( 22... Ra8 23. Nxb5 $18 ) ( 22... Rc8 23. Ng4 $1 h5 24. Rxc7+ $1 Kxc7 ( 24... Rxc7 $2 25. Nxe5+ Kb7 26. Nxb5 $18 ) 25. Nxb5+ Kb8 26. Nxe5 $16 ) 23. Ng4 $1 { [%csl Re5][%cal Rg4e5] } 23... Bb8 ( 23... h5 24. Rxc7+ $18 ) ( 23... Nc8 24. Ra8 Rd8 ) 24. Ra5 $16 { [%csl Rb5,Re5][%cal Ra5b5,Rg4e5] } 24... h5 25. Nf2 ( 25. Rxb5 $2 Na2+ $17 ( 25... hxg4 $2 26. Rxc5+ Kb7 27. Rb5 $18 ) ) 25... Ra7 26. Rxa7 Bxa7 27. Nh3 Nd7 28. Ng5 Nf8 29. g4 $1 ( 29. Nf7 Bb8 30. Nd8+ Kb6 31. Nb7 $5 Nd7 ) 29... g6 30. Nf7 Bb8 31. Bh6 Nd7 32. Nh8 $18 hxg4 33. fxg4 c4 34. bxc4 bxc4 35. Nxg6 Ba7 36. Bg7 Be3+ 37. Kd1 Kd6 38. h4 Nd5 39. exd5 exd5 40. Ke2 { 1-0 White wins. } 1-0
