1. d4 d6 2. e4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. dxe5 dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 6. Bc4 Be6 7. Bxe6 fxe6 8. Be3 Bb4 { [%cal Gb4c3] That is the better reaction. Black wants to force a concession. } 9. O-O-O+ { A good sign for Black. The knights cannot manoeuver as easily as in the previous game. And, White cannot use the a-file for the future. } 9... Nbd7 { The knight does not need to obstruct the c-pawn in this line. } 10. Nge2 Ke7 ( 10... Ng4 $5 11. Rd3 $1 ( 11. Bg5+ Be7 $1 ) 11... Ke7 ( 11... Nxe3 $1 12. Rxe3 Ke7 13. Rd1 g5 $5 ) 12. Bg5+ ( 12. Rhd1 Rhd8 13. Nb5 $6 Nxe3 ) 12... Ndf6 13. Rg3 $1 Kf7 14. h3 Nh6 15. Bxh6 gxh6 ) 11. f3 a6 12. Rd3 $14 ( 12. a3 Bc5 13. Bxc5+ Nxc5 $11 ) ( 12. Rd2 b5 { [%cal Gc7c5,Gc5c4] } ) ( 12. Nb1 Bc5 ) 12... c5 $6 ( { Simpler was } 12... b5 $1 { [%cal Gc6c5,Gc5c4] } 13. Rhd1 { and now not } 13... Nb6 ( { But } 13... Rhb8 $1 { as we know from before } 14. Nb1 Ke8 15. a3 ( 15. Nd2 Nc5 16. Bxc5 Bxc5 $13 ) 15... Be7 $13 ) 14. a3 $16 ) ( 12... Rhd8 ) 13. a3 $1 ( 13. Rhd1 c4 { [%csl Rd3] } ) 13... Ba5 14. Rhd1 Rhc8 ( { Browne believes that he has an edge in the line } 14... b5 $5 15. g4 $1 { but if we prolong the line a bit } 15... c4 16. Rd6 Rhd8 17. Rc6 Rdc8 18. Rdd6 $1 { we can see that Black can still hold as long as he trades a pair of rooks } 18... Rxc6 19. Rxc6 Nf8 $1 20. Bc5+ Kd7 21. Rd6+ Kc7 $11 ) ( { Another way to defend patienlty is } 14... c4 15. Rd6 Rac8 16. Kb1 ( 16. g4 Rhd8 17. h4 Nc5 18. Rxd8 Bxd8 19. h5 Bb6 $10 ) 16... Rhd8 ) 15. g4 $1 c4 ( 15... Nb6 $4 16. b4 $18 ) ( 15... Nf8 16. Na4 $5 c4 17. Rd6 Ne8 18. Bg5+ Kf7 19. Rb6 Rab8 ) 16. R3d2 Rc7 $6 ( { It was not too late to reduce the pressure along the d-file with } 16... Rd8 $1 17. h3 { f4 } ( 17. g5 $6 Nh5 18. f4 g6 $1 19. fxe5 Bc7 $1 ) 17... Nf8 { when Black should be still OK. } ) 17. h3 h6 18. f4 $1 exf4 19. Bxf4 e5 ( 19... Rc6 $4 20. e5 $18 ) 20. g5 $3 ( 20. Be3 Bb6 ( 20... Nc5 $2 21. Nd5+ Nxd5 22. Rxd5 $18 ) 21. Ng3 $5 ( 21. Rxd7+ Nxd7 22. Rxd7+ Rxd7 23. Bxb6 Ke6 24. Nd5 Rf8 25. Nc7+ $1 Kf7 