1. d4 {Bonus- a quick overview of the endgames without the doubling of the pawns. The pawn structure is more flexible, and if Black does not like to have structural defects, this might be your way to play it. The main problem could be the relatively shaky positon of the king in the center and the possible initiative along the -d and the -e files.But if Black is careful enough, he can maintain an equal position and may start outplaying the opponent. Most positional ideas we have seen in the previous game remain valid.} d6 2. e4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. dxe5 dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 6. Bc4 (6. f4 Bb4 7. Bd3 (7. Bd2 exf4 8. O-O-O Bg4 9. Nf3 Kc8 10. Bd3 Nbd7 11. Bxf4 Bxc3 12. bxc3 Nc5) 7... exf4 8. Bxf4 Be6 9. Nf3 (9. Nge2 $6 Nbd7 10. O-O-O Bd6 $1 11. Bb5 Bxf4+ 12. Nxf4 c6 13. Nxe6+ fxe6 14. Be2 Ke7 15. Kd2 Ne5 16. h3 g5 17. Ke3 h5 $15) 9... Nbd7 10. O-O-O Nh5 $5 11. Bg5+ Be7 12. Be3 Bc5 13. Bg5+ Kc8 14. Be2 h6 15. Bd2 Nhf6 $13 {[%cal Gf6g4,Gg4e5]}) (6. Nf3 Bd6 7. Bg5 (7. Ng5 Ke7 8. Bc4 Rf8 9. f4 exf4 10. e5 Bxe5 11. O-O Be6 12. Nxe6 fxe6 13. Bxf4 Bxf4 14. Rxf4 Nbd7 $15) (7. h3 Ke7 8. Be3 Be6 9. O-O-O Nbd7 10. Nd5+ Bxd5 (10... Ke8 11. Ng5 Bxd5 12. exd5) (10... Kf8 11. Ng5 Bxd5 12. exd5 g6) 11. exd5 a6) (7. Bc4 Ke8) 7... Be6 8. O-O-O (8. Bxf6+ gxf6 9. O-O-O Nd7) (8. Nb5 Nbd7 9. Nxd6 cxd6 10. Nd2 Rc8 11. c3 h6 12. Bh4 g5 13. Bg3 Ke7 {Najdorf Pawn Structure.} 14. f3 Nc5) 8... Nbd7 9. Bb5 (9. a3 $6 Kc8 10. h3 h6 11. Be3 Bc5 12. Kd2 Bxe3+ 13. Kxe3 c6 14. Ne2 Kc7 15. Rd2 b5 $15 {Positional grinding and improvement against slow play.}) (9. Bxf6+ gxf6 10. Nh4 Bc5 11. f3 (11. Rd2 c6 12. Na4 Bf8 13. Kb1 Kc7 14. Be2 b5 15. Nc3 Bb4 $15 {Dark-squared domination.}) 11... c6 12. Nf5 Kc7 13. Ng7 Bd4 14. Nxe6+ fxe6 15. Ne2 Be3+ 16. Kb1 h5 $36 {Opposite-colored bishop domination.}) 9... Kc8 10. Bxf6 Nxf6 11. Ng5 a6 12. Ba4 Bc4 13. Bb3 Bxb3 14. axb3 Rf8 15. Nd5 Nxd5 16. Rxd5 f6 17. Nf3 Kd7 18. Nd2 c6 19. Rd3 Ke6 {Draw in Moiseenko-Malaniuk.}) (6. Bg5 c6 (6... Be6 7. O-O-O+ Nbd7 8. Nf3 Bd6 9. Bb5) 7. f4 (7. Bc4 Ke8 8. O-O-O (8. f3 Nbd7 9. a4 (9. Nge2 b5 $1 10. Bd3 Nc5 11. Bxf6 gxf6 12. Ng3 Nxd3+ 13. cxd3 Rg8 14. Nd1 Be6 15. Ke2 Bc5 $15) 9... a5 10. Nge2 Nb6 11. Bb3 Nfd7 12. Rd1 f6 13. Be3 Bc5 $1 14. Kf2 Bxe3+ 15. Kxe3 Nc5 $15) 8... Nbd7 9. f3 h6 10. Be3 Bc5 $1 11. Bxc5 Nxc5 12. b4 Be6 13. Bxe6 Nxe6 14. Nge2 Ke7 {somewhat more pleasant symmetry for Black.}) 7... h6 8. O-O-O+ (8. Bxf6+ gxf6 9. Bc4 Be6 10. O-O-O+ Nd7 11. Bxe6 fxe6 12. fxe5 fxe5 13. Nge2 Rg8 14. Rhf1 Be7 15. g3 Ke8 16. a4 h5) 8... Kc7 9. Bxf6 gxf6 10. f5 (10. fxe5 fxe5 11. Bc4 f6 $5 12. Rf1 b5 13. Bf7 Nd7 14. Nf3 b4 15. Nd1 Ba6 16. Re1 Nc5 $15) 10... Bb4 11. Rd3 b6 12. a3 Bf8 13. Rh3 a5 14. a4 Ba6 15. Nf3 Bxf1 16. Rxf1 Na6 $13) (6. f3 Be6 7. Be3 Nbd7 8. O-O-O c6 9. g4 (9. g3 Bb4 10. Nce2 Kc7 11. Bh3 Rhe8 12. Bxe6 Rxe6 13. g4 Bc5 14. Bd2 a5 {Black is at minimum not worse.}) 9... Bb4 10. Nge2 Ke7 11. g5 Ne8 12. a3 Ba5 13. Na4 Nd6 14. Ng3 g6) 6... Ke8 $5 7. a3 (7. f3 {[%csl Ge8]} c6 {[%csl Gc6,Gb7,Ga7,Ge5][%cal Ge5d4,Gc6d5]} (7... Bb4 $5 {[%csl Gb4][%cal Gf2f3,Gc8e6,Gf7e6,Gb4c3]} 8. Nge2 Nbd7 $14 9. a3 Be7 10. Be3 c6 11. g4 Bc5 12. Bd2 h6 13. h4 Nf8 {[%cal Gg4g5]} 14. Ng3 Be6 15. Bd3 g6 16. O-O-O b5 17. h5 $14 {0-1 (60) Predke,A (2688) -Bortnyk, O (2604) Chess.com INT 2022}) (7... Bc5 8. Bg5 c6 9. Nge2 Ke7 (9... a5 $5 10. a4 Nfd7 {[%csl Gf6,Ge7][%cal Gf7f6,Ge8e7,Gd7b6,Gc8e6,Gb8d7,Gb8a6,Ga6b4]}) 10. Nc1 Be6 11. Bxe6 Kxe6 12. Nd3 Bd6 13. a4 a5 14. Be3 (14. O-O-O $14) 14... Nfd7 15. Ke2 Na6 16. Rhd1 Rhd8 17. b3 Ndc5 {1-0 (49) Lu,S (2615) -Lenderman,A (2624) Lichess.org INT 2020}) 8. Nge2 Bc5 9. Bd2 Nbd7 (9... a5 $5 10. a4 Na6) 10. a4 a5 11. Nc1 Ke7 12. Nd3 Bd6 13. Be3 Nf8 {[%cal Gd6c7,Gf8e6,Gc8e6]} 14. Nb1 Be6 15. Nd2 N6d7 16. Ke2 Bc7 17. Rhd1 Bxc4 18. Nxc4 Ne6 $14 {1-0 (90) Yu,Y (2739) -Rapport,R (2736) Hengshui 2019}) (7. f4 {[%csl Ge8][%cal Gf2f4]} Bd6 (7... Bb4 {[%csl Gb4][%cal Gf8d6,Gb4c3]} 8. Bd3 {[%cal Gc4d3]} Nbd7 9. Nf3 Nc5 {[%cal Gc5d3]} 10. Bd2 exf4 11. O-O-O Bxc3 (11... Be6 12. Rhe1 Nxd3+ 13. cx