1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. dxe5 dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 6. Bc4 Be6 7. Bxe6 fxe6 8. Be3 Bb4 (8... Nbd7 9. f3 Bb4 10. Nge2 Ke7 11. Bd2 a6 12. Nc1 Bd6 13. Nd1 Nb8 14. Nd3 Nc6 15. c4 $14 {Hodgson,J-Wyss,T/Bern op 1994}) 9. O-O-O+ Nbd7 10. Nge2 Ke7 11. f3 a6 (11... g6 12. g3 Bc5 13. Bxc5+ Nxc5 {1/2-1/2 Barlov,D-Aleksic,N/ Open 1998}) 12. a3 $6 {Bishop has nothing to do on b4, so there was no reason to lose time and weaken the king's position to make it come to a better place.} (12. Rd2 b5 13. Rhd1 Bd6 14. Kb1 Rhb8 15. Nc1 Nb6 16. Bxb6 Rxb6 {Rajlich, V-Rat,D/FSIMB March 2000}) 12... Bd6 (12... Bc5 13. Bxc5+ Nxc5 14. Ng3 Rad8 15. Nf1 Rxd1+ 16. Nxd1 g5 17. h3 h5 18. Nfe3 Ncd7 19. Nf2 Nf8 20. b4 Ng6 21. Nd3 Nd7 22. Nc4 {1/2-1/2 Sergejev,R-Neff,S/EST-chT 1996}) 13. g3 $6 {White doesn't find a plan and soon finds himself under the pressure. It's very hard to believe that white may lose this position in less than 20 moves without blundering, but that's exactly what is happening!} b5 14. Rhf1 Rhb8 $5 {Preparing Nb6.} 15. Nb1 $6 {Too passive: white decides that he has to defend, although Black isn't threatening.} (15. f4 b4 16. axb4 Rxb4 17. fxe5 Nxe5 18. Nd4 Kf7 (18... Rxb2 $2 19. Kxb2 Nc4+ 20. Ka1 Nxe3 21. e5 $16) 19. b3 $13) 15... c5 16. Nd2 c4 17. g4 Rc8 18. h3 a5 $36 {Now we can see the drawbacks of 12.a3} 19. f4 (19. Kb1 $5 b4 20. a4 c3 21. Nb3 cxb2 22. Kxb2 Nc5 23. Nxc5 Bxc5 24. Bxc5+ Rxc5 25. Rd3 Nd7 $15) 19... b4 20. g5 Nh5 21. axb4 (21. a4 c3 22. bxc3 bxc3 23. Nb3 Rc4 $15) 21... axb4 22. f5 Ra1+ 23. Nb1 Bc5 24. Rf3 (24. Kd2 Ra2 $1 25. Bxc5+ Nxc5 26. Ke3 Rxb2 $17) 24... Bxe3+ 25. Rxe3 Nc5 $17 {White is completely tied up, and the material losses are just a matter of time.} 26. Rf1 (26. h4 Nd3+ 27. cxd3 cxd3+ 28. Nec3 bxc3 29. bxc3 Rb8 $19) 26... Nd3+ $1 27. cxd3 cxd3+ 28. Nec3 (28. Kd2 dxe2 29. Rxe2 Ng3 $19) 28... bxc3 29. bxc3 Rb8 $19 30. Kd2 Nf4 31. Ree1 Rb2+ 32. Ke3 Ng2+ {0-1 Black wins.} 0-1

