{[#] Another example of a superior pawn structure in the Philidor. White's bishop and knight are horrible, whereas teh black pieces have room for improvement.} 21. Rd2 Nb6 22. Kf2 a5 $1 {Black can expand on both sides, ultimately opening files for the rooks. The rooks should be kept on the board, as the black ones can always find working files.} 23. Rb1 g6 24. Nd1 f5 {[%csl Ga5,Gf5][%cal Gh5h4]} 25. Bd3 Rd7 26. exf5 gxf5 27. Re2 Kf6 {[%csl Ge5,Gf5,Gf6]} 28. Ne3 Na4 29. Ree1 h4 30. Red1 Rhd8 31. Re1 Rg8 32. Nd1 Nc5 {[%csl Rd3][%cal Rd7d2] In the course of the game White had to abandon the d-file and now Black will use it.} 33. Bf1 f4 {[%csl Yd1,Rd4,Re3,Yf1,Rg3]} 34. Nc3 b4 $1 35. axb4 axb4 36. Ne4+ Nxe4+ 37. Rxe4 b3 38. cxb3 Bf5 {0-1 Black wins.} 0-1

