1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 Nbd7 4. Nf3 e5 5. Bc4 Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. Re1 c6 8. a4 b6 { [%csl Re4,Rd5][%cal Rf6e4,Rd6d5,Rc8b7] From White's perspective, one of the plausible plans is to try and plant a knight on the f5-square, thus making the best of his central superiority. } 9. Ba2 { [%csl Rc6,Rd5][%cal Gb7b6,Rd4d5] A semi-waiting and useful move. It is also related to the theory of the b7-b6 plan. } 9... Bb7 { The bishop is losing control over the vital f5-point, and we can use this instantly: } 10. dxe5 dxe5 ( 10... Nxe5 { [%cal Gf3e5] } 11. Nd4 $14 { [%cal Gd4f5,Gf2f4,Gh2h3] } ) 11. Nh4 { [%cal Rc8f5] Kasparov's Knight! The thirteenth world champion had an affection of this knight (that he was getting typically in the Ruy Lopez) and fully understood its strength. } 11... g6 ( 11... Nc5 12. Nf5 { [%cal Gd8d1,Gf5e7] } 12... Bc8 { Too late. } 13. Qf3 { [%cal Gf3g3,Gg3g7] } 13... Qc7 { Stellwagen-Gagunashvili, Amsterdam 2004 } 14. Qg3 ( 14. Nxe7+ Qxe7 15. Bg5 Be6 16. Bxf6 Qxf6 17. Qxf6 gxf6 $14 { Gagunashvili } 18. b4 Na6 ( 18... Nd7 19. Red1 ) 19. b5 { [%csl Rd5] Fight for the d5-square. } 19... cxb5 ( 19... Nb4 $1 { refutes White's plan. } ) 20. axb5 Nc5 21. Bd5 Bxd5 22. Nxd5 { [%csl Gd5] } ) ( 14. Bg5 $14 ) 14... Bxf5 15. exf5 { Good f5-pawn, kingside attack. } 15... Rfe8 16. Bh6 Bf8 17. Bg5 Be7 18. Bxf6 $1 { OCB favorable for White (Gagunashvili) } 18... Bxf6 19. b4 Nd7 20. Ne4 $16 { [%csl Ge4] } 20... Be7 21. Rad1 { [%csl Gd7][%cal Gf5f6] } 21... Red8 ( 21... Nf6 22. Bxf7+ Kxf7 23. Ng5+ Kg8 24. Ne6 { [%cal Gg3g7,Ge6c7,Ge6g7] } ) ( 21... Bxb4 22. Rxd7 { [%cal Ge4f6] } ( 22. f6 g6 23. Ng5 ) ( 22. Qb3 ) 22... Qxd7 23. Nf6+ $18 ) 22. h4 Bxb4 23. f6 ( 23. Ng5 ) 23... Bf8 24. Bxf7+ Kxf7 25. Qb3+ Kg6 26. h5+ Kxh5 ( 26... Kf5 27. Qf3+ Ke6 28. Ng5# ) 27. Qf7+ g6 28. Qxh7+ Bh6 29. Rd3 Rh8 30. Rh3+ Kg4 31. Qxg6+ Kf4 32. Rf3# ) ( 11... Bb4 12. Qf3 $14 ) ( 11... Nxe4 { [%csl Gh4] } 12. Rxe4 Bxh4 13. Rxh4 Qxh4 14. Qxd7 $16 ) 12. Bh6 Re8 13. Qf3 Bf8 14. Bg5 Bg7 15. Rad1 Qe7 ( 15... Bc8 16. Rd6 h6 17. Bxf6 Bxf6 18. Nxg6 Kg7 19. Nh4 { 1-0 Danin,A (2332) -Silivanov,S (2291) /St Petersburg 2004/CBM 102 } ) 16. Rxd7 Qxd7 17. Bxf6 Bxf6 18. Qxf6 $18 Qe7 19. Qxe7 Rxe7 20. Rd1 Kf8 21. Nf3 h6 22. h4 f6 23. Rd6 Kg7 24. h5 g5 25. Ne2 Rc7 26. Ng3 Rf8 27. Nf5+ Kh7 28. Nxe5 c5 29. Nd7 { 1-0 Bojkov, D (2475) -Trigo Urquijo,S (2062) / Erandio 2004/EXT 2006 } 1-0
