1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 Nbd7 4. Nf3 e5 5. Bc4 Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. Re1 c6 8. a4 b6 9. Ba2 a6 10. h3 Rb8 { [%csl Gf5,Gf6,Rb8][%cal Gc8f5,Gf3h4,Gf6e4] An attempt to avoid the line from the previous game, but this move also has a concrete drawback. } ( 10... Bb7 11. Nh4 exd4 12. Qxd4 d5 13. exd5 Nxd5 14. Nxd5 Bxh4 ( 14... cxd5 15. Nf5 Bf6 16. Qg4 Ne5 17. Qg3 $14 ) 15. Nc3 Bf6 16. Qd6 Nc5 17. Bf4 Qc8 ( 17... Bxc3 18. bxc3 Nxa4 19. Re7 Qxd6 20. Bxd6 Rad8 21. Bc7 Ra8 22. Be5 Bc8 23. Bd6 Bf5 24. Rc7 $16 ) ( 17... Re8 18. Qxd8 Raxd8 19. Bc7 Bxc3 20. bxc3 Rc8 21. Bxb6 Nxa4 22. Rxe8+ Rxe8 23. Bd4 c5 24. Bb3 cxd4 25. Bxa4 Rc8 ( 25... Rd8 26. Rd1 $16 ) 26. cxd4 Rc4 27. c3 Rxc3 $14 28. Rb1 Rc7 29. d5 $18 ) 18. a5 $16 { Kozakov-V. Georgiev, Croatia 2003. } ) 11. Nh4 $5 { This is again possible, based on a tactical nuance } 11... Nxe4 $2 { Now White's idea works. You can see how Black should play in the next file. } 12. Nxe4 Bxh4 13. Nxd6 Bxf2+ ( 13... Qf6 14. Ne4 Qg6 15. Qg4 Qxg4 16. hxg4 exd4 17. g5 $16 { [%cal Ga2g8] } ) 14. Kxf2 Qf6+ 15. Kg1 Qxd6 16. dxe5 $16 { [%csl Rb8] } 16... Qxd1 ( 16... Qc5+ 17. Kh1 Qb4 18. Bg5 Qxb2 19. Be7 Re8 { [%cal Ge7d6] } 20. Ba3 Qc3 21. Bxf7+ Kxf7 22. Qh5+ { [%csl Ge8][%cal Gh5e8] } ) 17. Rxd1 Rb7 ( { At last, we can see the drawback of the Ra8-b8 move in the line } 17... Nxe5 18. Bf4 { [%csl Rb8,Re5][%cal Rf4b8] } ) 18. e6 fxe6 19. Bxe6+ Kh8 $18 { White's advantage is overwhelming. } *
