{ White's position is better. The pawn on "d6" is weak. Black's counterplay is connected to the idea "d6-d5". Black's other idea is to play Nb4 or Nc5. } 12. Bxa6 $1 { [%csl Ra3,Yc8][%cal Ra3d6] Very strong move, the bishop on c4 was strong, but couldn't attack the pawn on "d6". Now the rook on "a6" will be misplaced. White plans to attack the weak pawn, and when all Black's pieces become passive to organize an attack against the king or to provoke more weaknesses. } 12... Rxa6 13. Qf3 Re8 14. h3 $1 { [%cal Ga1d1] Typical move which is preparing Rad1. } 14... Ra8 15. Rad1 Qc7 16. Qf4 $1 { [%csl Rd6][%cal Gf4d6,Ga3d6,Gd1d6] The "f4" square is the best for the queen. We keep "g3" for the rook. The other plan is 16.g4 followed by Qg3, Bc1-f4, but there is no need to weaken our king. } 16... Bf8 { [%cal Gd4e2,Gd4f3] } 17. Nf3 $1 { [%csl Yf6][%cal Rd1d3,Re1d1,Re4e5,Rf3e5,Re5f7,Bf3g5,Bf3h4,Bf3h2,Bh2g4] This is the ideal position for the knight. From here, he supports e4-e5 and can be transferred to c4 or the kingside. } 17... Rd8 18. Rd3 Be6 19. Red1 { [%cal Gf3d2,Gd2c4] } 19... Ne8 { Black manages to defend the pawn, but now all his pieces are very passive. } 20. Nd4 $1 { There is no good square for the "e6" bishop. } 20... g6 $2 ( 20... Bd7 21. Rf3 Nf6 22. Qg3 Ne8 23. Bc1 $1 ) ( 20... Bc8 { [%cal Ga8d8] } 21. Nce2 $1 { [%cal Ge2g3,Gg3f5,Gd4f5] The side that has space advantage can easily maneuver his pieces. The knight is not doing much on c3 and will be more useful on the kingside. } ( 21. Nde2 ) ) 21. Nxe6 fxe6 22. e5 $18 { That is game over. } 22... Qf7 23. Qxf7+ Kxf7 24. Ne4 h6 25. exd6 Kg8 26. Rg3 Kh7 27. Rf3 *
