[PlyCount "89"]
[SetUp "1"]
[WhiteElo "2749"]

{ [#] Whenever Black manages to break through with d6-d5, all the central pawns disappear and everything will depend on how the more active pieces are.This is not exactly the Philidor (the black bishop would be likely on e7 instead of on c5) , but the general ideas remain the same. } 17... Ndf4 { "I had a very promising position and also Alireza had like 15 minutes less than me so I was extremely optimistic" (Caruana) . Indeed, Black managed to bring his knights closer to the opponent's king much faster. Plus, his bishop on b6 is way more valuable than its counterpart on b5. } 18. Be3 c6 { The first moment in which Black could have grabbed the g2 pawn, starting a huge attack. Caruana sensed the importance of the situation and tried hard to find the follow-up. } ( 18... Nxg2 { "I couldn't make it work, but I wanted to play it. Every part of me wanted to take on g2. I assumed that it's not worse for Black or anything, and maybe it's very strong, but I didn't quite see how to follow up, and I thought: I shouldn't sac a piece without actually seeing the follow-up." (Caruana) After: } 19. Kxg2 Nh4+ ( 19... Qh4 $2 20. Qf3 { [%csl Gg3][%cal Gf3g3,Gg3h3] does not make sense for Black. } ) 20. Kh1 $1 ( 20. Kg1 { Which indeed leads to a decisive attack for Black after: } 20... Qd5 { [%cal Gd5g2] } 21. f3 Bxd4 22. Bxd4 Qg5+ 23. Kf2 Qg2+ 24. Ke3 { The exposed king cannot survive: } 24... Bf5 { [%cal Gc7c6,Gf8e8] is one way to reach it. } ( 24... c5 25. Bxc5 Qg5+ { [%csl Gc5][%cal Gg5c5] Regaining the material and attacking decisively. } ) ) 20... Qd5+ 21. f3 Bxh3 22. Nh2 Bg2+ 23. Kg1 Bh3 { [%cal Gd1e2,Gg1h1] } ) 19. Bc4 { Now, surprisingly, the situation changes in Black's favor. } ( 19. Be2 $1 ) 19... Bc7 ( 19... Nxg2 $3 { might have won since after: } 20. Kxg2 Qh4 $1 { From this side this time! White cannot adequately defend the h3 pawn, which means he will be slowly finished on the kingside. The concrete problem is that here: } 21. Qf3 ( 21. Nf3 Qxh3+ 22. Kg1 Rd8 23. Qe2 Bc7 { and the black pieces keep coming towards the enemy king: } 24. Rad1 Bg4 { with a win. } ) 21... Ne5 { [%csl Rc4,Rf3] } ) 20. Ng3 { Now Firouzja stabilizes his kingside. It is important to mention that he speeded up at this part of the game. } 20... Nd5 ( 20... Nxg2 $5 21. Kxg2 Qh4 { Now an excellent defensive idea is: } 22. Bf1 $1 Bxh3+ 23. Kg1 Bxg3 { With another important in-between move: } 24. Nf3 $1 ( 24. fxg3 Qxg3+ 25. Kh1 Bxf1 { when Black is winning. } ) 24... Qg4 25. Bxh3 Qxh3 26. fxg3 Qxg3+ 27. Kh1 { and objectively it should be about equal. } ) 21. Bd2 Qd6 { Now it is also equal, but the time spent in the opening from both opponents will soon start to tell. } 22. Bb3 Bd7 23. Nf3 Rfe8 24. Qc2 Ngf4 25. Rad1 Rxe1+ 26. Rxe1 Qf6 27. Nd4 { Time for Firouzja to look for the f5 spot. } 27... Rd8 28. Re4 Qg6 { Caruana called this a mistake, but was it really? } ( 28... c5 $5 29. Ndf5 ( 29. Nf3 Bc6 ) 29... b6 ) 29. Bxd5 Nxd5 30. Ngf5 $1 { missed by Caruana. } 30... Qf6 ( 30... Bxf5 31. Nxf5 Qxf5 32. Re8+ ) 31. Rg4 { Caruana's time pressure prevents him of finding the best defence. } 31... g6 ( 31... Kh8 $3 { Would have stopped the attack for good as the pawn is immune: } 32. Rxg7 $2 c5 33. Bxh6 cxd4 { wins for Black. } ) 32. Nxh6+ Kf8 $1 { Best defense now by Caruana. } ( 32... Kg7 33. Bg5 Qd6 34. Rg3 ( 34. Bf4 ) ) 33. Re4 $1 { Best play by the younger GM. } ( 33. Bg5 Qd6 34. Bxd8 ( 34. Rg3 Re8 $1 ) 34... Qh2+ 35. Kf1 Qh1+ 36. Ke2 Bxg4+ 37. Nxg4 Bxd8 { and White cannot keep his extra pawn. } ) 33... Nf4 34. Ng4 Bxg4 35. hxg4 Kg7 36. Bxf4 { White forces matter in the time-trouble. } ( 36. Nf3 $1 { kicking the enemy knight back after g2-g3 with close to won position. } ) 36... Bxf4 37. Nf5+ gxf5 38. Rxf4 Qg5 39. Rxf5 ( 39. Qxf5 $4 Rd1+ 40. Kh2 Qh4# ) ( 39. g3 fxg4 40. Qe4 { might have been a good alternative. } ) 39... Qxg4 40. Rf3 Qh5 41. c4 { Time control is over, Firouzja is up a solid pawn and has good pieces. It all seems a matter of technique now. } ( 41. Rd3 $1 ) 41... Rd4 { Now the American GM gets some initiative. } 42. Qc3 Qe5 43. Rd3 { Firouzja wants to swap off the rooks, rather than the queens. } ( 43. g3 Rd1+ 44. Kg2 Qxc3 45. Rxc3 ) 43... c5 $1 { But Caruana wants something in return. } 44. Rg3+ ( 44. Rxd4 cxd4 { and Black should survive here. } ) 44... Kf8 45. Qxa5 { The Second pawn goes down, but for a moment the queen abandons her king, giving Black a chance to create nasty threats. } 45... Rd1+ 46. Kh2 Qh5+ 47. Rh3 Qe5+ 48. g3 { It seems over, but Caruana had calculated everything carefully. } 48... Qf5 $3 { "I was lucky to have ...Qf5. It was a miracle." (Caruana) Black sacrifices a third pawn, with a check! But it is far more important to stick to the vital pawn on f2, the pawn that stands on the road of his major pieces and the white king. } 49. Qa8+ Ke7 ( 49... Kg7 $4 50. Qh8+ Kg6 51. Qh6# ) 50. Qxb7+ Rd7 51. Qh1 $5 { The last try to avoid the draw. } ( 51. Qg2 Rd2 52. Kg1 Qb1+ 53. Kh2 Qf5 { with repetition. } ) 51... Qxf2+ 52. Qg2 Rd2 53. Qxf2 Rxf2+ 54. Kg1 Rxb2 55. Rh5 Ra2 { but a notoriously drawish rook endgame appears on the board and Caruana holds. } 56. Rxc5 Rxa4 57. Kg2 Kd6 58. Rd5+ Ke6 59. Rd4 Ke5 60. Rf4 f5 61. Kh3 Ra3 { 1/2-1/2 The game is a draw. } 1/2-1/2
