1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. d3 Nc6 4. c3 { [%cal Gb2b4] White starts playing against the c6-knight. At the same time, the move c2-c3 supports the queenside expansion which usually starts with b2-b4. } 4... a5 { It is useful to prevent b2-b4. } ( 4... d5 5. Nbd2 Be7 { [%csl Ge7] White can immediately gain space on the queenside by } ( 5... Bc5 6. b4 { [%csl Ge5,Rb4,Rb6][%cal Gb4b5,Gf3e5,Re4d5,Rc3c4,Rc4c5] } ) 6. b4 { with a comfortable position, for example: } 6... a6 { In one of his games, Kasparov played } 7. a3 { which is also quite interesting. } ( 7. Be2 { when the critical position arises after } 7... O-O 8. O-O h6 9. Bb2 Be6 10. a3 Re8 11. Qc2 { [%csl Gb4,Gc3,Ga3,Re5,Yd5,Bc4][%cal Gc3c4,Gb4b5,Ga3a4,Rf3e5,Ye4d5,Bb2e5,Gf1e1,Ge2f1,Ge1e5] } 11... dxe4 { At some point, Black has to go for this concession. The reason is that White can follow with Re1 and Bf1, thus putting indirect pressure on the e5-pawn. His idea would be exd5 followed by c3-c4. } 12. dxe4 { [%csl Ge2,Gc3,Gb4,Ga3][%cal Ge2a6,Ge2h5,Ge2c4] With colours reversed, we have reached the Pirc structure. This time, however, White has two important advantages: 1) the bishop is on e2, instead of g2 2) White has already gained space on the queenside. We are already familiar with the plans in this pawn structure. Let's take a look at how White won in this game: } 12... Nd7 13. Rfd1 Bg5 14. c4 Qf6 15. Nb3 Rad8 16. b5 axb5 17. cxb5 Bxb3 18. Qxb3 Ncb8 19. g3 { [%cal Gh2h4] } 19... Qg6 20. Qc2 Qb6 21. a4 c5 22. a5 Qc7 23. Rd5 Bf6 24. Nd2 Nf8 25. Rxc5 $18 { 1-0 Hickl,J (2540) -Sinkovics,P (2330) / Biel 1992/ (36) } ) 7... O-O 8. Be2 b6 9. O-O Bb7 10. Qc2 Re8 11. Re1 $1 { [%csl Ge7] Once again, we have the same idea. Putting pressure on e5 by means of Re1 followed by Bf1. The idea is to provoke the move ...dxe4. } 11... Bf8 { [%cal Ge2f1,Gg2g3,Gf1g2,Gg7g6,Gf8g7] } 12. Bf1 { [%cal Ge5d5,Gd5d4,Gd4e4,Ge4e5] } 12... g6 13. Bb2 Bg7 { Black's play is quite logical. By transferring the bishop to g7, he overprotects the e5-pawn. White, however, has an additional resource at his disposal - } 14. a4 { [%csl Re5][%cal Gb4b5] The idea of b4-b5 forces Black to release the central tension. } 14... dxe4 ( 14... d4 15. cxd4 { [%csl Gd4][%cal Gc6d4] } 15... Nxd4 16. Nxd4 exd4 { [%csl Gf2,Gg2,Gh2,Ge4,Rf7,Rh7,Rg6,Rd4][%cal Gf2f4,Ge4e5,Gh2h3,Gd2b3,Gb2d4] } ) 15. dxe4 { [%csl Gc6][%cal Gb7e4,Gb4b5,Ge6e5] Once again, we have the same structure! } 15... Nh5 16. Nc4 { [%csl Rd5][%cal Gc4e3,Ge3d5,Yc6d4] Kasparov transfers the knight to d5. } 16... Qf6 17. Ne3 Ne7 18. c4 Nc6 { [%cal Gc6d4] } 19. Nd5 Qd8 { 1-0 Kasparov,G (2825) -Zarnicki,P (2515) /Internet ICC 1998/ (56) White is clearly better. At this point, he should have followed with } 20. Red1 $5 Nd4 $14 21. Nxd4 exd4 22. b5 axb5 23. axb5 { [%csl Rd4,Gd3,Gd5][%cal Gf1d3,Gg2g3,Gf2f4,Ge4e5] when the d4-pawn will be lost. } ) 5. Be2 g6 { As we have seen, putting the bishop on g7 is quite logical in this structure. } ( 5... d5 6. Nbd2 Be7 7. O-O O-O 8. Qc2 Re8 { [%cal Gb2b4] } 9. b3 $1 { [%cal Gc1b2,Ga2a3,Gb3b4] This move is an important part of White's strategy. White prepares to expand on the queenside by means of Bb2 and a2-a3 followed by b3-b4. } 9... Bf8 10. Bb2 h6 11. a3 g6 12. Rfe1 $1 { [%cal Ge2f1] Once again, we see this typical pattern - Re1 followed by Bf1. } 12... Bg7 13. Bf1 b6 14. Rac1 Ba6 15. b4 dxe4 16. dxe4 Bxf1 17. Nxf1 { Finally, White managed to get this favourable pawn structure. As is often the case, the c6-knight creates big co-ordination problems for Black. } 17... Qe7 18. Ne3 Qe6 19. h3 Ne7 20. c4 $1 { We know this typical idea from the game of Kasparov. The idea is to follow with Nd5. This move is good when Black cannot make use of the d4-square. } 20... axb4 21. axb4 Ra2 22. Qb1 Rxb2 { This is a desperation. } 23. Qxb2 Nxe4 24. Nd5 Nxd5 25. cxd5 Qxd5 26. Rxc7 $16 { 1-0 Gavrikov,V (2552) -Toikka,J/Jyvaskyla 1999/ (43) } ) 6. O-O Bg7 7. Qc2 ( 7. Nbd2 ) 7... O-O 8. Nbd2 d5 ( 8... d6 { and then prepare f7-f5. } ) 9. b3 h6 ( 9... b6 10. Bb2 ( 10. Re1 $5 Ba6 11. Bf1 dxe4 $14 12. dxe4 Bxf1 13. Nxf1 ) 10... Ba6 11. Rfe1 dxe4 12. dxe4 Bxe2 13. Rxe2 Nh5 14. Nc4 Nf4 { 1/2 Tompa,J (2400) -Lukacs,P (2460) / Budapest 1978 } ) 10. Bb2 b6 11. Rfe1 Bb7 12. a3 Re8 13. Bf1 { White wants to force the exchange on e4 which opens diagonal for the f1-bishop and gives the c4-square for d2-knight. } 13... dxe4 14. dxe4 Nb8 $5 { Black relocates this knight to d7 increasing his control over the d5-square. } 15. b4 Nbd7 16. Nc4 { Now White is interested in exchange on b4 when the reply cxb4 will activate the b2-bishop. } 16... Ra7 { [%csl Ge4][%cal Gd8a8,Ga8a1,Ga8e4] In this situation, Black has problems finding a reasonable plan of play. } ( 16... Qe7 ) 17. Nfd2 $1 { A typical move. The idea is to "kill" Black's minor pieces by means of f2-f3. } ( 17. bxa5 $6 bxa5 ) 17... Qa8 18. f3 { [%csl Gg2,Gf3,Ge4,Rb7] } 18... Bc6 19. Ne3 Bf8 20. Rac1 { Since White is ready to recapture on b4 with the c-pawn, the rook is well placed on c1. } 20... Bb7 21. Rcd1 c6 ( 21... Bc6 ) 22. Ndc4 { [%cal Gc4d6] } 22... Qb8 23. Qf2 ( 23. Rd2 Ba8 24. Red1 { then } 24... axb4 25. cxb4 b5 26. Na5 c5 $13 ) 23... Ba6 24. Qh4 $5 { Planning Ng4. } 24... Bb5 ( 24... h5 $5 ) 25. Ng4 Nxg4 26. Qxg4 Re6 27. Qh4 h5 28. Qf2 axb4 29. cxb4 Ba4 30. Rc1 b5 ( 30... c5 31. Bc3 $13 ( 31. bxc5 Bxc5 32. Ne3 Bc6 ) ) 31. Ne3 c5 $2 { Weakens without necessity the d5-square. } ( 31... Rc7 ) 32. Nd5 c4 ( 32... cxb4 $6 33. axb4 $16 Nb6 $14 34. f4 $1 ) 33. g3 $1 Bh6 $6 ( 33... Bg7 ) 34. f4 exf4 35. gxf4 Nb6 $2 { The decisive mistake in a time-trouble. } ( 35... Bg7 36. Bh3 Rea6 { keeping the defensive possibilities. } ) 36. Qd4 Kh7 37. Nf6+ Rxf6 38. Qxf6 $18 Rd7 39. Bh3 Qd8 40. Bxd7 Qxf6 41. Bxf6 Nxd7 42. Bg5 { 1-0 White wins. } 1-0
