1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. g4 $5 {Regarding the Shirov line, Black's main answer remains the principled capture. GM Kapnisis explained the main dangers for the second player in the next two games well. It should be added that the risk is worth it, and one can safely accept the sacrifice.} Nxg4 6. Rg1 Ngf6 7. Be3 c6 8. Qd2 b5 (8... exd4 $2 {Opening the centre is illogical given that White is way ahead in development.} 9. Nxd4 Nc5 10. f3 Qe7 11. O-O-O Be6 (11... Bd7 12. b4 $1 Na6 13. Bxa6 bxa6 14. Qd3 $18) (11... g6 {[#]} 12. Ndb5 $1 (12. e5 $5 dxe5 13. Nxc6 bxc6 14. Bxc5 Qc7 15. Bxf8 Rxf8 16. Qg5 $16) 12... cxb5 13. e5 Qxe5 14. Re1 {White is completely winning}) 12. Nxe6 Qxe6 13. Bxc5 $1 dxc5 14. e5 $18 {1-0 (25) Oparin,G (2613) -Maslak,K (2555) St Petersburg RUS 2018}) (8... g6 $5 {In my opinion, this is a move that hasn't been tried that much and deserves more attention.} 9. O-O-O Qe7 10. Ng5 {White provokes h6, making it difficult for Black to castle.} (10. dxe5 dxe5 11. Bc4 Bg7 12. Bh6 $2 O-O $2 {[#]} (12... Bxh6 $1 13. Qxh6 Nb6 14. Bb3 Bg4 $17 (14... Be6 $5)) 13. Nh4 $1 Nxe4 (13... Nb6 14. Nxg6 $1 hxg6 15. Rxg6 Ne8 16. Bb3 $18) 14. Nxg6 hxg6 15. Nxe4 $18 {1-0 (21) Nguyen,T (2399) -Neuman,P (2427) Czech Republic CZE 2015}) 10... h6 (10... Bg7 11. dxe5 dxe5 (11... Nxe5 12. f4 $16) 12. f4 O-O 13. f5 $44 {White's attack looks too strong in my eyes.}) 11. Nf3 Bg7 (11... Nh5 12. Kb1 Bg7) 12. dxe5 (12. a4 exd4 $5 (12... b6 {1-0 (27) Giri,A (2730) -Driessens, P (2342) Netherland NED 2013}) 13. Bxd4 O-O $13 14. Nh4 Ne5 15. f4 Nfg4 $1 16. fxe5 Qxh4 17. exd6 Ne5 $17) 12... dxe5 (12... Nxe5 $2 13. Nxe5 dxe5 14. Bc5 $18) 13. a4 Nh5 14. Kb1 Nf4 (14... Qf6 15. Ne1 Nf4 16. Nd3 Ne6 $13) 15. Bc4 Nb6 16. Bb3 Be6 17. a5 Nd7 18. Nd5 $13) 9. O-O-O Qa5 $1 (9... Bb7 $2 {A normal developing move can be a serious mistake. Both White and Black should be very alert to tactical possibilities, like sacrifices on b5.} 10. dxe5 dxe5 {[#]} (10... b4 11. exf6 bxc3 12. Qxc3 $18) (10... Nxe5 11. Nxe5 dxe5 12. Nxb5 $16) 11. Nxb5 $1 cxb5 (11... Nxe4 12. Qe2 (12. Qe1 cxb5 13. Bxb5 $18) 12... cxb5 13. Nxe5 $18) 12. Bxb5 Qc7 13. Nxe5 O-O-O 14. Nxf7 $18) (9... b4 $2 10. dxe5 $1 {Another piece sacrifice gives White a dangerous attack.} dxe5 {[#]} (10... bxc3 11. Qxc3 dxe5 12. Bc4 Nxe4 13. Bxf7+ Kxf7 14. Qxc6 Rb8 15. Qxe4 Qe7 16. Ng5+ Ke8 17. Qc6 $18) 11. Bc4 $1 (11. Nxe5 bxc3 12. Qxc3 $44) 11... Qa5 $1 (11... Qc7 12. Ng5 $18) 12. Nb5 $1 cxb5 13. Bd5 Rb8 14. Ng5 h6 15. Nxf7 Rh7 (15... Nxd5 16. Qxd5 Nf6 17. Qb3 $16) 16. f4 $16) 10. dxe5 dxe5 (10... Nxe5 11. Nxe5 dxe5 {[#]} 12. Rg5 $1 {An unusual rook lift which adds fuel to White's attack} (12. f4 Be6 13. f5 Bd7 $13 {1-0 (32) Zufic,M (2439) -Muskardin,M (2216) Bosnjaci CRO 2013}) 12... Be7 13. Bc5 $1 (13. Rxe5 Be6 14. Bh3 $1 Rd8 15. Bd4 Qc7 $13) 13... Bxc5 14. Rxe5+ Be6 (14... Be7 15. Rxe7+ $1 Kxe7 16. Nd5+ $18) 15. Rxc5 O-O 16. Bd3 $14) 11. Bh3 (11. Kb1 $1 {This is the main line and I think there is no reason to avoid it with White.} h6 $5 (11... b4 {[#]} 12. Na4 $1 h6 (12... Bb7 13. b3 O-O-O $2 (13... h6 14. Qe2 $36) 14. Ng5 $18 {1-0 (26) Dastan,B (2441) -Gajek,R (2391) Karpacz POL 2015}) (12... Nxe4 13. Qd3 Nd6 14. Qb3 $16) (12... Qxa4 $2 13. Nxe5 $1 Be7 {[#]} (13... b3 14. axb3 Qxe4 (14... Qb4 15. Qxb4 Bxb4 16. Nxc6 $18) 15. Bd4 $18) 14. Nxf7 $1 O-O (14... Kxf7 15. Bc4+ Kf8 (15... Ke8 16. Rxg7 $18) 16. Rxg7 $18) 15. Nh6+ (15. Rxg7+ $5 Kxg7 16. Bc4 Rxf7 17. Bh6+ Kh8 18. Bxf7 Nf8 19. Rg1 $16) 15... Kh8 16. Bd4 $18 {is completely winning for White}) 13. b3 $5 (13. Bc4 Ba6 $1 14. Bxa6 Qxa6 15. b3 $44 {0-1 (30) Fercec,N (2461) -Halvax,G (2395) Zadar CRO 2016})) (11... g6 $6 {[#]} 12. Rg5 $1 Be7 13. Rxe5 $1 {Even stronger than Nxe5.} (13. Nxe5 Nxe5 14. Rxe5 Be6 {is not so clear.}) 13... Nxe5 14. Nxe5 Qc7 (14... Bb7 15. Bh6 $1 Rd8 16. Nd5 Qxd2 17. Nc7# {is a nice diagram}) (14... b4 15. Nxc6 bxc3 16. Qd4 Qc7 17. Nxe7 Qxe7 18. Bg5 $16) 15. Bf4 $18) 12. Qe1 $5 Qc7 $2 {[#]} (12... g5 $6 13. h4 g4 14. Nd4 $1 exd4 15. Bxd4 Bg7 16. e5 O-O 17. exf6 $44) (12... b4 13. Ne2 Ba6 (13... g6 14. Nd2 $44) 14. Nc1 $44 {Black still has problems with the security of his king while White will try to take advantage of the weakened c4 square.}) (12... g6 {[#]} 13. Nxe5 $5 {One of the main ideas of 12.Qe1.} (13. Nd4 exd4 14. Bxd4 Bg7 15. e5 O-O (15... Nd5 16. Bg2 $16 (16. e6 $40)) 16. exf6 Nxf6 17. Bxf6 Bxf6 18. Ne4 Qxe1 19. Nxf6+ Kg7 20. Nh5+ Kh8 21. Rxe1 gxh5 {is equal}) 13... Nxe5 14. Nd5 (14. Nxb5 $2 Bb4 $19) 14... Qd8 15. Nb6 $13) 13. Bxb5 $1 {Another sacrifice on b5!} cxb5 14. Nxb5 Qc4 15. Qa5 $16 {1/2 (0) Lagunow,R (2420) -Kraus,T (2463) Radenci SLO 2019}) 11... b4 (11... Qc7 $5) 12. Nb1 Qc7 13. Bxd7+ $2 (13. Qe2 {Getting the knight to c4 should be the right plan for White.} g6 14. Nbd2 Bg7 15. Nc4 O-O 16. Nd6 {White has reasonable compensation.}) 13... Nxd7 (13... Bxd7 14. Rg5 Be6 15. Rxe5 Be7 {Black is fine.}) 14. Nh4 g6 15. f4 Nb6 $6 (15... c5 $5 16. Qf2 c4 $17) 16. b3 Be7 17. Nf3 c5 18. Nxe5 Bb7 (18... f6 $5) (18... Be6 $5) 19. Qe2 c4 (19... Bxe4 20. Qb5+ Kf8 $17) 20. Bxb6 (20. Ng4 $13) 20... Qxb6 (20... axb6 21. Rd7 Qc5 22. Rgd1 $13) 21. Qxc4 $2 (21. Nxc4 $14) 21... O-O 22. Rg3 Rac8 23. Qe2 Rfd8 (23... Qf6 $17) 24. Rxd8+ Rxd8 25. Rd3 Kg7 (25... Rxd3 $17) 26. Rxd8 Bxd8 27. Qd3 Qg1+ $17 28. Kb2 Bb6 29. a3 Qd4+ 30. c3 Qf2+ 31. Qd2 Qxd2+ 32. Nxd2 Be3 33. Nec4 bxc3+ 34. Kxc3 Bxf4 35. h4 h5 36. Kd4 g5 37. hxg5 h4 38. Nf3 h3 39. a4 Bc8 40. Ne3 h2 41. Nxh2 Bxh2 42. Nd1 Bg1+ 43. Ke5 Kg6 44. Nc3 Kxg5 45. b4 Be6 46. a5 Bc4 47. Nd5 Bf2 48. Kd6 Bd3 49. e5 Bg3 50. Ke7 Bxe5 51. Kxf7 Bc4 52. Ke6 Bg3 53. b5 Kg4 54. b6 a6 {0-1 Black wins.} 0-1

