1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. Bc4 Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. a4 c6 8. Re1 b6 { This is the starting position of the main line with b6. Black's idea is very simple. He is trying to develop the light-squared bishop and gain space on the queenside by means of a7-a6 followed by Bb7 and b6-b5. In the meantime, Black is stopping the a4-a5 advance. This system was always very popular choice for Black, but has one serious drawback. It weakens the light squares and White can start a fight for these squares by playing 9.d4-d5. The arising positions are quite complex, with chances for both sides. } *
