1. e4 d6 { In this game we shall check the typical Najdorf/Classical Sicilian type of pawn structure that arises in the b7-b6 line. } ( { Another opening in which we can see a similar structure is the Yates Ruy Lopez } 1... e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O b5 6. Bb3 Be7 7. c3 d6 8. d4 { [%csl Gd4] } ( 8. Re1 O-O 9. d4 Bg4 10. d5 Na5 11. Bc2 c6 { [%csl Gc6] } 12. dxc6 ) ) 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. Bc4 Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. Re1 c6 { [%cal Gb7b5] } 8. a4 { [%csl Rc6,Rb7][%cal Gb7b6,Ga7a6,Gc8b7,Gb6b5,Gh7h6,Gf8e8,Gf3g5] } 8... Qc7 9. h3 b6 10. d5 { [%csl Rc6][%cal Gb7b6] One of the main moves. This game illustrates the dangers when facing a light-squared strategy. } 10... Bb7 ( 10... c5 11. a5 Bb7 12. a6 Bc8 13. Bb5 ) 11. dxc6 Bxc6 12. Bg5 h6 $6 { A mistake. Black is facilitating his opponent's plan. Better was: } ( 12... Bxe4 $5 13. Rxe4 ( 13. Nxe4 Qxc4 14. Nxd6 Bxd6 15. Qxd6 Qxc2 16. Nxe5 Nxe5 17. Qxe5 Rae8 { should also hold for Black. } ) 13... Nxe4 14. Nxe4 Qxc4 15. Bxe7 Qxe4 16. Qxd6 Nc5 17. Bxf8 Rxf8 18. Qd2 f6 19. a5 b5 20. Rd1 a6 21. Qc3 Qc4 { was drawn in the game J. Benjamin-L. Kristiansen, USA 1997. } ) 13. Bxf6 Nxf6 14. Qe2 a6 { [%cal Ga7a6] } 15. Rad1 ( { White is also somewhat better after } 15. Bxa6 $5 Nxe4 16. Nxe4 Bxe4 17. Qxe4 Rxa6 18. c4 $14 { [%cal Gf7f5,Gg7g5,Gf5f4,Ge5e4,Ge7f6] but this is playable. } ) 15... Bb7 ( { Missing another concrete chance } 15... Bxa4 $1 16. Nxa4 b5 17. Bb3 bxa4 18. Bxa4 a5 $13 { [%cal Gb8b2,Gc8c2] } ) 16. Nh4 $1 { [%csl Rh6,Rf5,Rg6][%cal Rh7h6,Yh4g6,Yh4f5] } 16... Rfc8 ( 16... Nxe4 $2 { [%cal Be7h4] } 17. Nxe4 Bxh4 18. Nxd6 Bf6 19. Nxb7 Qxb7 20. Bd5 ) 17. Nf5 Bf8 18. Bb3 g6 $6 19. Ne3 $1 { [%csl Rb3,Rc3,Re3,Rf3,Yf8][%cal Rf3h4,Rh4f5,Rf5e3,Rb3d5,Re3d5] The ideal set-up fr the first player. White got everything that he wanted, the d5-square is under full control. } 19... Rab8 ( 19... Nxe4 20. Nxe4 Bxe4 21. Qg4 { [%cal Rb3g8,Rg4g6] } 21... Qb7 22. f3 $18 ) 20. Rd3 b5 21. axb5 axb5 22. Ng4 Nh5 23. Qd2 $1 { A difficult move, based on a flashy combinational motif. } 23... Nf4 24. Rf3 Qa5 25. g3 { An elegant finish. } ( 25. Rxf4 exf4 26. Qxf4 { [%csl Rf7] } 26... Qc7 27. Nxh6+ Bxh6 28. Qxh6 { [%cal Rh6g6,Gb3g8] wins as well. } ) 25... Nxh3+ { [%csl Rf7,Rh6] } 26. Kg2 Ng5 27. Qxg5 $3 hxg5 28. Nf6+ Kg7 29. Rh1 { [%csl Rg7,Rf6,Rf3][%cal Gh1h7,Rh7g7,Rb3g8] 1-0 White wins. } 29... Be7 30. Rh7+ Kf8 31. Rxf7# { [%csl Rb3,Gf6,Gf7,Gf3] } 1-0
