1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 {Tang decided to surprise his well-prepared opponent and deviated from his usual open games.} 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. Bc4 Be7 {"The Philidor was a surprise, but not a very unpleasant one, because White gets a nice position most of the time." (Dominguez)} 6. a4 O-O 7. O-O c6 8. Re1 h6 {[%cal Gh7h6] A relatively rare continuation.} (8... a5 $5) (8... b6 {are more common, and more chanceful for Black.}) 9. a5 $1 {[%csl Rd5,Ra6][%cal Ra5a6,Rd4d5] Whenever White can, he should grab as much space on the queenside. This move not only deprivesthe black queen of active spots on the queenside, but it palso repares a timely destruction of the opponent's pawn chain.} Qc7 (9... Re8 10. h3 exd4 11. Qxd4 Ne5 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Gf3e5,Gd6e5]} 12. Be2 (12. Nxe5 dxe5 13. Qxe5 Bd6 {[%csl Re5]}) 12... Ng6 13. Be3 Bf8 14. b4 Qc7 {[%csl Gh6,Rc3][%cal Ge3h6,Gg7h6,Gd4f6,Gf8g7,Gg7c3]} 15. b5 Be6 16. a6 {[%csl Rb7,Rc6] with very sharp play, Duda,J (2732) -Rapport,R (2752) Berlin 2023}) 10. h3 Re8 11. Ba2 {[%cal Rd7e5,Re5c4] Both sides are making useful moves, the bishop moves away from the possible d6-d5 and/or Nd7-e5 tempi.} Bf8 {[#] This one is perhaps not as useful, as Black may need the f8-square for the rook sometimes.} (11... Rb8 $5 12. Be3 b5 13. axb6 axb6 {[%cal Gd4d5]} 14. d5 cxd5 15. Nxd5 Nxd5 16. Qxd5 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Ge8f8]} Rf8 $1) 12. Bd2 $14 {A careful move, and a novelty.} (12. Nh4 {[%cal Rd8h4,Gh4f5] but after} exd4 13. Qxd4 {Black missed the strong} d5 $1 {[%csl Re1][%cal Ge8e1]} (13... Nc5 14. Bf4 Ne6 15. Bxe6 Bxe6 16. e5 {provided White some pressure, Slizhevsky,A (2426) -Petrova,I (2087) Chess.com INT 2020})) (12. Be3 {was completely possible, to which Black likely intended} exd4 13. Bxd4 Ne5 {[%csl Re4][%cal Ge8e5,Ge5f3]}) 12... Rb8 13. d5 {The pawn structure now changes and it will look more like a Najdorf/Ruy Lopez Yates line than anything else.} b5 (13... cxd5 14. Nxd5 Nxd5 15. Bxd5 {[%csl Gb7,Ga7][%cal Gd7f6,Gc8e6] avoiding the creation of extra queenside weaknesses for the time being.}) 14. dxc6 Qxc6 {[%cal Gb2b4] Dominguez was happy with the game's outcome, which he considered advantageous, riskfree.} 15. Nh2 (15. b4 $5 {[%csl Rd7][%cal Rb4c5,Ra5b6,Rc8d7] which would have deprived the black Nd7 of any squares, but then decided that there is nothing to be afraid of b5-b4 advance.}) 15... Bb7 (15... b4 {was also possible when the position evaluation does not change much after} 16. Nd5 Nxd5 17. Bxd5 Qc7 18. Qf3) 16. Ng4 {[%csl Rb7,Rd7,Rf6,Yf8]} b4 {The only active try.} 17. Nxf6+ {And Dominguez decided to play slowly.} (17. Nd5 Nxd5 18. Bxd5 Qc7 {he will have a decisive blow with} 19. Nxh6+ gxh6 20. Qg4+ {but once that b5-b4 happened on the board, Dominguez realized that this line is not clear, for instance} Kh8 21. Bxf7 Nf6 22. Qg6 Re7 $1 23. Bb3 Bg7 24. Bxh6 Bxh6 25. Qxh6+ Nh7 {and Black defends.}) 17... Nxf6 18. Nd5 Nxd5 19. Bxd5 Qc7 20. Bb3 $1 {An excellent move, this bishop is far superior that its counterpart. Actually, both white bishops are.} (20. Bxb7 Qxb7 21. a6 Qc7) 20... Bc6 21. a6 Be7 {[%cal Ge7g5] A blunder.} (21... Red8 22. Qf3 Qd7 23. Be3 {True, White is still better here.}) 22. Qh5 {And a miss.} (22. Qg4 $1 {[%cal Gd2h6] instead would have put Black into an awkward situation, it is not clear how to defend against the simple threat of Bd2xh6!} Kf8 23. Qf5 {[%csl Gf7][%cal Gf5f7]} Bd8 24. Qh7 {looks winning for White.} (24. Rad1 {with the idea} Kg8 25. Bxh6 $1 gxh6 26. Qg6+ Kf8 27. Qxh6+ {[%csl Gd6][%cal Gf8g8,Gd1d6,Gd6g6]} Ke7 28. Bxf7 $3 Kxf7 29. Rxd6 {[%csl Rc6][%cal Gd6c6,Rh6h7,Ge1e3,Ge3f3] and a winning attack.})) 22... Bf6 23. Be3 Red8 24. Qg4 Kf8 (24... Qd7 $5 25. Qf3 Qe7 $5 {intending to swap off the dark-squared bishops.}) 25. Red1 {White's play is simple and strong, he simply aims the weak points in the enemy camp.} Bb5 (25... Qd7 $5 26. Qf3 Qe7 {was better.}) 26. Qf3 Bg5 {So, finally Tang managed to swap off the weaker of his two bishops.} 27. Bxg5 hxg5 28. Qh5 {But this swap came at the price of a pawn.} Bc4 (28... f6 $2 29. Qh8+ {[%cal Gh8g7]}) 29. Qxg5 Bxb3 30. cxb3 Qc2 {A desperate counterattack in the time-trouble.} (30... Rb6 {should not have changed the outcome of the game.}) 31. Qe3 Qxb2 32. Qxa7 Qxb3 {Tang restores the material balance.} 33. Rxd6 $1 {Simple trick, but effective.} Rdc8 34. Qd7 (34. Rc6 $5 {looked good too.}) 34... Qc3 35. Rad1 b3 36. a7 Ra8 37. Qb7 Kg8 (37... b2 {changes nothing due to} 38. Rd7) 38. Rd7 Qc2 {And while making his last move, Black lost on time.} (38... Qc4 39. Rb1 {he was dropping another pawn.}) (38... Qc2 39. Rf1 Qc4 {Rf8 Rxf7!} 40. Rb1 {transpoing to the line from above.}) 1-0

