1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. Bc4 Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. a4 c6 8. Re1 b6 { It is time to have a look at the main ideas in the b7-b6 line. For starters, the most direct approach. } 9. d5 { [%csl Rc6][%cal Rb7b6] Huzman: 'This central advance is a typical motif for White in the Philidor Defence. } 9... cxd5 ( 9... Bb7 $5 { is the other main line. } ) ( 9... c5 $6 { should be avoided, as after } 10. a5 { [%cal Ga5a6] } 10... a6 11. axb6 Nxb6 12. Bf1 $16 { [%csl Ra6][%cal Gf3d2,Gd2c4,Gb2b4,Gc1e3,Ga5a6] White gets everything that he wants in the center and on the queenside. } ) 10. Nxd5 ( { The other recapture is also possible } 10. Bxd5 Nxd5 11. Nxd5 ( { Less convincing is } 11. Qxd5 Ba6 ( 11... Rb8 ) 12. Be3 Rc8 13. a5 Bc4 14. Qd2 bxa5 $1 15. b3 Be6 16. Nb5 Nc5 17. Nxa7 Nxe4 18. Qd3 Nc5 19. Qb5 Rc7 20. Nc6 Qd7 21. Nxe7+ Qxe7 22. Qxa5 Rfc8 $15 { 0-1 Hnydiuk, A-Pedzich,D/ Czestochowa 1998/EXT 2000 (32) } ) 11... Nf6 { [%csl Ge7,Rf3,Gf6][%cal Gc1g5,Gc2c4,Gb2b3,Rf3d5] Challenging the center at once. This would be our grand strategy. We want to ensure that White would not have the time to transfer his Nf3 to the optimal d5-square as it happened in my game against Krum Georgiev. } 12. Nxe7+ ( 12. c4 { A new move, that can hardly aspire to an advantage. Relatively, the most promising continuation is 12.Nxf6+, but with precise play, Black should be able to equalize.' (Huzman, Ftachnik) } 12... Nxd5 13. exd5 $6 ( 13. Qxd5 Be6 { [%csl Rf3,Ge6][%cal Rf3d5] } 14. Qd3 Qc8 { [%cal Ge6c4,Gc8c4] } 15. b3 f5 $13 { [%csl Ge6][%cal Gf5e4] } ( 15... Qb7 $5 { [%cal Ga7a6,Gb6b5,Gg7g6,Gf7f5,Gd6d5] postponing the break on the light-squares for the time being. } ) ) 13... Bg4 $15 { Huzman,A: 'The position of Black is much better due to the pair of bishops and the possibility of the pawn advances f5 and e4.' } ( 13... a5 $1 { is simpler, and stronger. The black pawn majority can easily get into motion on the kingside, whereas White is blocked for good. } ) 14. a5 Qd7 ( 14... Qc7 $5 ) 15. Qa4 $2 { Huzman,A: 'This move doesn't prevent the planned break of pawns chain c4-d5 but helps it.' } ( 15. h3 Bf5 ( 15... Bh5 $2 16. Nxe5 $18 ) 16. Be3 $13 ) 15... b5 $1 { Huzman,A: 'Ftacnik: 'A very impressive small combination. Azmaiparashvili is not satisfied with simple equality and instead tries for an active play. '' } ( 15... Qb7 $4 { that they both suggest is actually a blunder due to } 16. c5 $1 { [%csl Rg4][%cal Ga4g4,Rc5c6] } ) 16. Qxb5 ( 16. cxb5 Rfb8 17. b6 axb6 $17 ) 16... Qxb5 17. cxb5 Rfb8 18. b6 ( 18. Nd4 $1 Kf8 19. Nc6 Rxb5 $17 ) 18... axb6 19. a6 $2 ( 19. Nd4 $5 Bd7 ( 19... exd4 20. Rxe7 bxa5 21. Re4 Bd7 22. Rxd4 a4 23. h3 ) 20. a6 Rc8 21. Bd2 Kf8 $15 ) 19... Bc8 $17 20. a7 ( 20. Nd4 Bxa6 ( 20... Rxa6 21. Rxa6 Bxa6 22. Nc6 Rb7 23. Be3 $44 ) 21. Nc6 Re8 22. Be3 Bf6 23. Bxb6 Bc4 $17 ) 20... Rb7 21. Be3 Rbxa7 22. Rac1 ( 22. Rxa7 Rxa7 23. Bxb6 Rb7 24. Rc1 Bf5 25. Rc6 Kf8 $5 ( 25... Be4 26. Rc8+ Bf8 27. Nd2 Bxd5 28. Bc7 Be6 29. Rxf8+ Kxf8 30. Bxd6+ Ke8 31. Bxe5 f6 $17 ) 26. b4 Bd7 27. Ba5 Rb5 28. Rc7 Rxd5 $19 ) 22... Bb7 23. Bxb6 Ra6 24. Bc7 Bxd5 $19 25. b4 Bc6 26. Nd4 exd4 $1 27. Rxe7 d3 28. Rd1 Ra1 $1 29. Ree1 Rxd1 30. Rxd1 Ra2 31. f3 d2 32. Kf2 Ba4 33. Ke2 Bxd1+ 34. Kxd1 d5 35. Be5 f6 36. Bd4 Kf7 37. g4 Ke6 38. h4 Ra3 39. f4 Rd3 40. f5+ Kd7 41. Bc5 Rg3 { 0-1 (41) Polgar,J (2722) -Azmaiparashvili,Z (2693) Benidorm 2003 Opening Encyclopaedia 22 [Huzman] } ) ( 12. Nxf6+ Bxf6 { [%csl Rf3][%cal Rf4f3] Since the white knight is far away from the vital d5-point, White cannot fix any advantage. We shall see this idea working repeatedly for Black. } 13. c4 { 'd5' } ( 13. Ra3 $6 Ba6 ( 13... Be7 $5 14. Rd3 Ba6 15. Rd2 Qc7 16. c3 Rad8 $15 ) ) ( 13. b3 $2 d5 $6 ( 13... Bb7 ) 14. exd5 $2 ( 14. Ba3 $1 Re8 15. Qxd5 Qxd5 16. exd5 Bf5 17. Rac1 e4 18. Nd2 $44 ) 14... e4 { [%cal Gf3d4,Gd8d5] } ) 13... Bb7 ( 13... Be6 14. b3 Be7 15. Ba3 $14 { Even this is actually equal after } 15... a6 $1 16. Qd3 b5 $1 17. axb5 ( 17. cxb5 axb5 18. Qxb5 Rb8 ) 17... axb5 18. cxb5 Qb6 ) 14. b3 ( 14. Qd3 { Nd2 } 14... Be7 15. Nd2 Qd7 16. Nf1 f5 $13 ) 14... Be7 15. Qd3 ( 15. Ba3 f5 16. Nd2 Qd7 ( 16... Bh4 17. Ra2 Qf6 18. Nf3 Bxf2+ 19. Rxf2 fxe4 20. Qxd6 exf3 21. Qxe5 Qxe5 22. Rxe5 Rfe8 { 57 1/2-1/2 Gyimesi, Z-Ruck,R/Budapest 1996/ } ) 17. Ra2 Rad8 18. f3 fxe4 19. Nxe4 ( 19. fxe4 $2 Bh4 20. Re2 Qg4 $19 ) 19... d5 $1 20. Bxe7 Qxe7 21. cxd5 Rxd5 { Kalod,R (2455) -Jansa,V (2490) /Zlin 1997 } ) 15... Qc8 $1 ( 15... Qc7 $5 16. Ba3 ( 16. Bb2 $5 g6 17. Rad1 f5 $13 ) 16... f5 17. Nd2 $5 ( 17. exf5 Qc6 $1 18. Rad1 Rae8 $13 ) ) ( 15... f5 16. exf5 Bf6 ( 16... Qc7 17. Ng5 ) ( 16... e4 17. Rxe4 $1 Bxe4 18. Qxe4 Qd7 ( 18... Bf6 19. Rb1 { Inf.16...Bf6 } ) 19. Bb2 ( 19. Ba3 $5 ) 19... Rae8 20. Qd5+ Kh8 21. g4 Bf6 22. Bxf6 Rxf6 23. Rd1 $14 ) 17. Rb1 e4 18. Rxe4 Bxe4 19. Qxe4 { Inf.16...Bf6 } 19... Qe7 ( 19... Qe8 20. Qd3 ) 20. Qd3 ( 20. Qd5+ $6 Qf7 ) 20... Rfe8 21. Ba3 Rad8 22. Kf1 $44 { Huzman,A: '1-0 Acs, P-Conquest,S/ Bled 2002/EXT 2003 (42) ' } 22... Qb7 ( 22... Qe4 23. Rd1 ) 23. Rd1 Re4 24. Qd5+ ( 24. Bxd6 $2 Be7 $19 ) 24... Qxd5 25. Rxd5 h5 ( 25... Kf7 26. Bxd6 Be7 27. Re5 $18 ) ( 25... Rde8 26. Bxd6 ( 26. h3 h5 ) 26... Re2 27. g4 Rb2 28. Rb5 $1 ( 28. Rd3 $6 Rd8 29. Nd2 Be5 ) 28... Rd8 ( 28... Ree2 29. Bg3 $16 ) 29. c5 $16 ) 26. Bxd6 $1 { 1-0 Acs,P (2591) -Conquest,S (2537) /Bled olm 2002 (42) Huzman: ' ' Huzman: '1-0 Acs, P-Conquest,S/Bled 2002/EXT 2003 (42) ' } ( 26. g3 ) ) 16. Nd2 f5 17. exf5 Rxf5 18. Ne4 Qe6 $13 ) ( 12. b3 $5 Nxd5 13. Qxd5 Be6 14. Qd3 h6 { [%cal Ge7g5,Gf3d2,Ga8c8,Gd8c7,Ga7a6,Gb6b5] } ( 14... Qc7 ) ) 12... Qxe7 { [%csl Gd5] } 13. c4 ( 13. Bg5 { [%cal Gh7h6] } 13... h6 { [%cal Gc8b7] } 14. Bxf6 Qxf6 15. Qd3 ( 15. Nd2 Be6 ( 15... Bb7 $1 { [%csl Re4,Rd5,Ye3][%cal Rd2c4,Rc4e3,Re3d5,Rb7e4,Yd2f1,Yf1e3] } 16. Nc4 ( 16. Nf1 Rad8 17. c4 Qe6 18. Qc2 f5 $13 ) 16... Rfd8 ) 16. Nf1 Rfd8 17. Ne3 Rac8 18. Qd3 Qe7 19. c4 Qc7 20. b3 a6 21. Red1 Qc5 22. Nd5 $14 { Khruschiov, A-Strikovic, A/Internet section 16-B/ 2003/ Huzman,A: 'Khruschiov,A-Strikovic,A/ Internet section 16-B/ 2003/' } ) 15... Bb7 16. c4 Qe7 17. Nd2 f5 18. exf5 Qg5 19. Ne4 Qxf5 { 1/2-1/2 Bitalzadeh, A-Ellenbroek,T/Dieren NED 2003/ (76) } ) 13... Bb7 14. Nd2 a6 { [%cal Gb7h1,Gb6b5,Gg7g6,Gf7f5,Gd6d5] } 15. b3 Bc6 ( 15... b5 ) 16. Ba3 Rfd8 17. Qc2 Qb7 18. Rac1 Rac8 19. Qd3 Nd7 20. Qe3 { 1/2-1/2 (20) Van Kampen,R (2560) -Reinderman,D (2598) Amsterdam 2012 } ) 10... Nxd5 { I find this to be the simplest solution. Black needs to fight for the control over the d5-spot ASAP. } 11. Bxd5 Rb8 { [%cal Rd7f6] Next the plan is to expel the bishop from the d5 square, or trade it, and look for counterplay related to the b6-b5, f7-f5 and above all d6-d5 breaks in the spirit of the Sveshnikov Sicilian. Black is often gaining the bishop pair as well, when from the two bishops the more valuable is the light-squared one and this is the bishop that provides more than enough compensation for the damaged pawn structure. } 12. b3 ( { The other possibilities do not change the character of the position. } 12. c3 Nf6 13. Bb3 Bb7 14. Qd3 h6 15. h3 Rc8 16. Nh2 Rc5 { [%csl Rd5][%cal Gd8a8,Ga8e4,Rh2f1,Rf1e3,Re3d5] } 17. Ng4 Nxg4 18. hxg4 Bg5 19. Be3 Bxe3 20. Rxe3 Qg5 { Kaiumov,D-Panchenko,A/ Cheliabinsk 1993 (40) } ) ( { Or } 12. Qd3 Qc7 13. Be3 Nf6 { [%csl Rc2,Rd5][%cal Rc7c2,Rf6d5] } 14. Bb3 h6 { [%csl Gf6,Gd5,Re4][%cal Gf6e4,Gc8b7] } 15. Bd2 Nd7 16. Bb4 Nc5 17. Bxc5 dxc5 ( { Here correct is } 17... bxc5 $13 { [%csl Gf3,Gb4,Re4,Ra6][%cal Gb8b4,Gc5c4,Gb4d4,Rc8b7,Rb7e4,Rb7a6] in order to look for dynamical unbalances that favor the bishops } ) 18. Bd5 $14 { 1/2-1/2 Kindermann, S-Schmidt Schaeffer,S/Munich op9293 1993 (41) } ) ( 12. Nd2 { [%cal Gd2f1,Gf1e3] } 12... Nf6 13. Nc4 Nxd5 14. Qxd5 Be6 15. Qd3 Rc8 ( 15... f5 $1 16. exf5 Bxf5 $13 ) 16. Ne3 Bg5 17. c3 Bxe3 18. Bxe3 Qc7 19. f3 Rfd8 20. Qe2 d5 $13 { 0-1 Koscielski, J-Blauert,J/ Dortmund op 1995 (35) } ) ( { Now let's have a look at a model game from Black's perspective, again by GM Reinderman: } 12. h3 Nf6 13. b3 $6 Nxd5 14. Qxd5 Bb7 15. Qd3 f5 $1 { One of the planned breaks, the easier one to execute, but probably the most chanceful } 16. exf5 Bf6 { [%cal Ge5e4] } ( { Not letting the game dry after } 16... e4 $6 17. Rxe4 $1 Bxe4 18. Qxe4 $44 { [%cal Gc1b2,Ga1d1] } ) 17. Qe3 Bxf3 ( 17... Qd7 $5 18. Ba3 Bxf3 19. gxf3 Be7 $17 { [%cal Gd7f5] } ) 18. gxf3 Rb7 { The pawn chain has been fixed in Black's favor, the white king is eternally weak, which means that Black can simply prepare a decisive kingside attack. } 19. Ba3 Rbf7 20. Rad1 Be7 21. f4 Rxf5 22. Bb2 Qe8 23. fxe5 Qg6+ 24. Kh1 Rf3 25. Rg1 Qh5 26. Rxg7+ Kxg7 27. exd6+ Bf6 28. Qe7+ Qf7 29. Qxf7+ Kxf7 { 0-1 (29) Sukandar,I (2408) -Reinderman,D (2582) Amsterdam 2020 } ) 12... Nf6 13. Ba3 ( { Or } 13. Bc4 Bb7 { [%csl Re4][%cal Gd6d5] } ( 13... a6 { [%cal Gb6b5,Gc8e6,Gd6d5,Gc8b7] } ) ) 13... Nxd5 14. Qxd5 Bb7 { [%cal Ga8h1] The most aggressive position for the bishop. } ( { The other development of the bishop } 14... Be6 { is perfectly playable as well } 15. Qd3 Qe8 16. c4 Rd8 17. Nd2 f5 18. exf5 Bxf5 19. Ne4 Qf7 ( 19... Qg6 ) ) 15. Qd3 Qc7 16. c4 Rbd8 17. Nd2 f5 18. exf5 Qd7 19. Rad1 Rxf5 20. Ne4 Rf4 { White's better pawn structure and blockade are compensated by the powerful black pieces. } 21. Bc1 Rg4 22. f3 Rg6 23. Nc3 $2 { Misses a powerful blow. } 23... Bg5 { Alas, so does Black. } ( { Black's strategy could have been crowned with } 23... Rxg2+ $3 { [%csl Gb7][%cal Gd7g4,Gg4f3,Gd8f8,Ge7h4] } 24. Kxg2 Qg4+ 25. Kf1 ( 25. Kf2 Bh4+ 26. Ke2 ( 26. Ke3 Qf4+ 27. Ke2 Qxh2+ ) 26... Qg2+ 27. Ke3 Qf2# ) 25... Qh3+ 26. Kg1 Bxf3 27. Rd2 Qg4+ 28. Kf1 Rf8 29. Rf2 Bh4 $19 ) 24. Bxg5 Rxg5 25. Kh1 Kh8 26. Nb5 d5 27. cxd5 Qxd5 28. Qc2 Qg8 29. Qc7 Rb8 30. Nd6 h6 31. Nf7+ Kh7 32. Nxg5+ hxg5 33. Qxe5 Kh6 34. Rd6+ g6 35. h4 { 1-0 (35) Timman,J (2565) -Reinderman,D (2568) Amstelveen 2016 } 1-0
