1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. Bc4 Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. a4 c6 8. Re1 b6 9. b3 { Another main approach against the b7-b6 line. For now, White postpones the decision-making in the center and prefers to keep the tension. } 9... Bb7 ( 9... a6 10. d5 ) 10. Bb2 { There are plenty of other possibilities: } ( { The immediate queenside advance } 10. a5 { [%cal Ga5a6] Huzman: 'White is threatening to push the Bb7 by 11.a6 now. Another idea of the last move is to open the a-file.' After } 10... b5 11. a6 { I suggest } ( 11. Bd3 a6 ) 11... Bxa6 $14 12. Rxa6 ( 12. Bxf7+ Rxf7 13. Rxa6 Qc8 ) 12... bxc4 13. Rxc6 cxb3 14. cxb3 Rc8 $11 ) ( { White can also add more tension in the center with } 10. Ba3 { when } 10... Re8 { overprotecting the bishop is sensible. Then after } ( { The moves can be transposed as usual in the Philidor } 10... a6 { [%cal Gb6b5] } 11. Bd3 c5 ( 11... Re8 $13 { [%csl Rc3][%cal Ge7f8,Ge8e4] } ) 12. dxe5 Nxe5 13. Nxe5 dxe5 14. Bc4 $16 { [%cal Gc3d5] } ( 14. Qe2 $16 ) 14... Qc7 15. Qe2 Rfd8 16. Rad1 { [%csl Gd5] Dreev,A (2698) -Azmaiparashvili,Z (2672) chessassistantclub.com INT 2004 } ) 11. d5 { Now make sure you avoid the locking of the queenside } 11... c5 $2 ( { Black needs to switch back to the ideas from the previous file } 11... cxd5 $5 12. Nxd5 Nxd5 13. Bxd5 Bxd5 14. Qxd5 { Two sets of light pieces are traded, and White does not have enough control after } 14... Nf6 15. Qd2 a6 16. Rad1 Ra7 { [%csl Rf3][%cal Ga7d7,Gb6b5,Gd8a8,Rf3d5] } ) 12. a5 a6 13. axb6 Nxb6 $16 { Macieja, B-Stocek,J/CZE 2001/ EXT 2002 (38) } ) ( { If } 10. d5 cxd5 11. Nxd5 Rc8 $1 { [%cal Rc8c2,Gf6d5,Gc4d5,Gb7d5,Rd1d5,Ge4d5] Puts pressure against the c2-pawn and forces White to make a decision regarding tehe Nd5. For example } 12. Nxf6+ ( { Or } 12. Re2 Nc5 { [%csl Re4] } 13. Nxf6+ Bxf6 14. Bd5 Bxd5 15. Qxd5 { And now an important maneuver to add to your knowledge base } 15... Ne6 $1 { [%csl Re2,Rd5][%cal Ge6c7,Ge6f4] } 16. Be3 Nc7 $1 { [%csl Rd5][%cal Rd6d5,Rc7d5] } 17. Qd3 d5 $15 { Flear,G (2471) -Mamedov,R (2660) Bastia 2011 } ) 12... Nxf6 { [%cal Gf3d2,Gd6d5] } 13. Bd3 d5 $1 14. exd5 e4 $1 15. Bxe4 Nxe4 16. Rxe4 Bf6 17. Ra2 Bxd5 18. Re1 Bc3 19. Re3 Bxb3 $19 { 0-1 Sprenger, J-Bratanov,Z/Metz 2002/ } ) ( 10. Bf1 { is harmless } 10... a6 { [%cal Gb6b5] } ) ( { is met with the already well-known } 10. Nh4 exd4 $1 11. Qxd4 d5 $1 12. exd5 cxd5 $13 13. Nxd5 $4 Nxd5 { [%csl Rh4,Gd8,Ge7] } ) 10... a6 { This is the most useful move. Black prepares b6-b5 in a good moment. } ( { It is not yet certain if the queen will belong to c7- } 10... Qc7 11. Bd3 Rfe8 12. Ne2 Bf8 13. Ng3 Rad8 14. c4 exd4 15. Nxd4 a5 ( 15... d5 $1 ) 16. Rc1 g6 17. f4 $14 { Brunello,M (2337) -Peng,L (2517) Reykjavik 2022 } ) 11. Bd3 { [%csl Ge4][%cal Rb6b5,Rd6d5,Gd3e4] Prophilaxys against both b6-b5 and d6-d5 ideas. Carlsen also overprotects the e4-pawn, an important part of his plan. } ( { The alternatives did not yield White anything so far: } 11. Qd2 b5 ( 11... Qc7 12. Rad1 Rad8 13. Bd3 Rfe8 14. Ne2 Bf8 ( 14... d5 $1 ) 15. Ng3 g6 16. h4 Bg7 17. h5 Ng4 18. Qg5 Ndf6 19. dxe5 dxe5 20. Qh4 $14 { 0-1 Hauchard,A-Seret,J/ Cappelle la Grande FRA 2004/ (32) Huzman: '0-1 Hauchard, A-Seret,J/Cappelle la Grande FRA 2004/ (32) ' } ) ( 11... Re8 $5 12. Rad1 b5 13. Bf1 Bf8 14. dxe5 Nxe5 15. Nxe5 dxe5 ) 12. axb5 axb5 13. Bd3 Rxa1 14. Bxa1 Re8 15. Ne2 Bf8 16. Ng3 g6 17. Bc3 Qc7 18. h4 h5 $1 19. Qc1 Ng4 20. Qb2 $2 Qb6 ( 20... exd4 $1 21. Nxd4 ( 21. Bxd4 c5 22. Bc3 b4 23. Bd2 Bg7 $17 ) 21... b4 $1 22. Bd2 Bg7 $19 ) 21. b4 Bg7 22. Re2 Ra8 23. Nf1 Ra4 $17 { Buksa,N (2414) -Bologan,V (2574) Chess.com INT 2021 } ) ( { Or the solid } 11. Bf1 { which however exposes the e4 pawn. Black is doing great after } 11... Re8 12. g3 ( 12. Qd3 Bf8 13. g3 { This whole plan is dubious. } 13... Qc7 14. Bh3 Rad8 15. Nh4 $6 b5 16. axb5 axb5 17. Bg2 b4 18. Nd1 $2 ( 18. Ne2 d5 $17 ) 18... d5 $5 ( 18... exd4 $1 19. Bxd4 ( 19. f4 c5 $17 ) 19... c5 20. Bb2 d5 $17 ) 19. exd5 e4 20. Qd2 cxd5 $15 { Coelho,L (2235) -Soto Vega,J (2386) /Sao Paulo 2001 } ) ( 12. Qd2 Bf8 13. Rad1 g6 14. h3 Qc7 15. Ba3 Rad8 16. dxe5 dxe5 ( 16... Nxe5 $1 17. Nxe5 ( 17. Nh2 b5 ) 17... dxe5 18. Qc1 Bxa3 19. Qxa3 ) 17. Bxf8 Nxf8 18. Qg5 N6d7 19. Rd2 f6 20. Qh4 ( 20. Qe3 $1 { hoping for some tiny edge. } ) 20... Kg7 21. Nh2 Nc5 22. Ng4 Qe7 { Peptan, C-Dworakowska,J/ Ostrava 1999/CBM 70 ext/1/ 2-1/2 (63) } ) 12... Bf8 13. Bg2 Qc7 ( 13... b5 14. axb5 axb5 15. Nb1 Qc7 16. Nbd2 g6 17. c4 exd4 18. Nxd4 bxc4 19. Nxc4 d5 20. exd5 cxd5 21. Rxe8 Rxe8 22. Ne3 Bc5 23. Rc1 Qb6 { 0-1 Trindade, S-Vasquez,R/Sao Paulo 1993/CBM 36 (36) } ) 14. Qd3 b5 15. Rad1 Rad8 16. h3 b4 17. Nb1 exd4 18. Nxd4 Nc5 19. Qd2 Ncxe4 $17 { Sawadkuhi,M-Pribyl,J/ Pardubice 2000/EXT 2001 (30) Huzman } 20. Qf4 Nd5 21. Qh4 { 1/2-1/2 Sawadkuhi, M-Pribyl,J/ Pardubice 2000/EXT 2001 (30) } ) ( 11. d5 cxd5 12. Nxd5 Nc5 ( 12... Nxd5 13. Bxd5 Qc7 14. c4 ( 14. Bxb7 Qxb7 15. Ba3 Rfd8 ) 14... b5 $13 ) 13. Nxf6+ Bxf6 14. Bd5 Qd7 15. c4 Bxd5 $1 16. cxd5 b5 17. a5 Rac8 18. Ba3 Rc7 19. Bb4 Rfc8 20. h3 Bd8 21. Re3 f5 22. exf5 Qxf5 23. Nd2 Bg5 24. Rf3 Qg6 25. Rg3 Qh6 26. Bxc5 Rxc5 27. Nf1 Bf4 28. Rd3 e4 29. Rd4 Be5 30. Rxe4 Bxa1 31. Qxa1 Rc1 32. Qd4 Rb1 { 0-1 (32) Kanep,M (2485) -Ruck,R (2561) Tallinn 2016 } ) 11... Re8 { [%csl Re4,Gc3][%cal Gf8g7,Ge7f8,Gg7g6,Gd6d5,Ge5d4,Gc6c5,Gb7e4] Cuenca plans to fianchetto his dark-squared bishop, in the spirit of the Breyer Ruy Lopez, but while doing this allows White a chance to coordinate perfectly his pieces. } ( { The accurate move order } 11... g6 $1 { [%csl Rg6,Ge8][%cal Rf8e8,Rg7g6,Ge7f8,Gf8g7,Gb6b5,Gd8c7,Rc3e2,Re2g3] provides Black excellent play. It is needed, in order to meet } 12. Ne2 $6 { with } ( { If } 12. Qd2 Re8 { [%cal Ge7f8] } 13. Rad1 Bf8 { [%csl Rc3] } ( 13... exd4 14. Nxd4 Bf8 15. Nf3 b5 $13 ) ( 13... b5 $13 ) 14. dxe5 dxe5 15. Ne2 b5 16. axb5 $6 cxb5 { [%cal Rb7e4,Rf6e4] } 17. Ng3 Qb6 18. h3 a5 19. Bc3 Bc6 $17 { [%csl Gb5,Ga5,Rg3,Yc3,Yd3][%cal Gb6g1,Gc6e4,Ba5a4,Ba4a3,Ba3a2] Socko,B (2615) -Azmaiparashvili,Z (2672) Ermioni Argolidas 2005 } ) 12... exd4 13. Bxd4 ( 13. Nexd4 c5 $1 { [%csl Re8,Rf5][%cal Gf6e4,Rd4f5,Rf8e8] is the main point. } ) 13... c5 { [%csl Re4] } 14. Bxf6 Bxf6 15. Rb1 Re8 ( { Black would do even better with } 15... Ne5 $1 16. Nf4 Re8 17. Nd5 Bxd5 18. exd5 Qd7 19. Nxe5 Bxe5 $15 { [%csl Ra4,Rb3,Rc2,Rd3,Rd5,Ge5][%cal Rd3c2,Rd3c4,Rc4d5,Ge5h2] Favourable OCB in Efimenko,Z (2660) -Markowski, T (2598) Plovdiv 2008 } ) 16. Nf4 Bc3 $17 { Navara, D (2722) -Kabanov,N (2520) Khanty-Mansiysk 2011 } ) 12. Ne2 $1 { The point! White solves the problem of his awkward knight (see the game Gavrikov-Bareev for details) } ( 12. Nb1 Bf8 13. Nbd2 Qc7 14. c3 Rad8 ( 14... d5 $1 { [%csl Gc3][%cal Gc2c3,Gb2c3] } ) 15. Qc2 g6 16. Rad1 Qb8 17. Bf1 Qa8 18. h3 Be7 19. Qb1 exd4 20. cxd4 d5 21. e5 $14 Nh5 22. e6 fxe6 23. Rxe6 Ng7 24. Ree1 Bb4 25. Qc1 Rxe1 26. Nxe1 Re8 27. Nd3 Bf8 28. a5 bxa5 29. Qc3 Qd8 30. Ra1 Ne6 { 1/2-1/2 (30) Godena,M (2551) -Salgado Lopez,I (2595) Khanty-Mansiysk 2010 } ) 12... Bf8 ( { Here } 12... d5 { does not work concretely due to } 13. Ng3 $1 { [%cal Gg3f5] } ( 13. dxe5 Nxe4 14. Ng3 Nxg3 15. hxg3 Nc5 ) 13... dxe4 14. Nxe4 exd4 15. Nxd4 { [%csl Gd4,Ge4][%cal Gd4f5] } 15... c5 16. Nf5 Bxe4 17. Bxe4 Nxe4 18. Nxg7 $1 Bd6 ( 18... Bf6 19. Nxe8 Bxb2 20. Rxe4 $18 { [%cal Gd1g4,Gg4g7,Gd1a1,Ga1g7] } ) 19. Qf3 $1 Ng5 ( 19... Ne5 20. Qxe4 Kxg7 21. f4 f6 22. fxe5 Bxe5 23. Bxe5 Rxe5 24. Qb7+ Kh8 25. Rad1 Rxe1+ 26. Rxe1 $16 ) 20. Rxe8+ Qxe8 21. Qd5 Qe4 22. Qxg5 Bf4 23. Qf5 $16 ) 13. Ng3 { White is perfectly prepared to gain the initiative on both flanks. } 13... g6 ( 13... b5 14. h3 Qc7 15. Qd2 g6 16. c4 bxc4 17. Bxc4 Bg7 18. dxe5 Nxe5 19. Nxe5 dxe5 20. b4 $16 { Svidler,P (2723) -Cuenca Jimenez,J (2535) chess24.com INT 2020 } ) ( 13... Qc7 $5 ) 14. Qd2 ( 14. c3 Qc7 ( 14... Bg7 15. b4 Qc7 16. Qb3 Re7 17. Rad1 Rae8 18. dxe5 Nxe5 19. Nxe5 dxe5 20. Bb1 Rd8 21. Rxd8+ Qxd8 22. Ba2 Bh6 23. Rd1 Qc7 24. f3 Bc8 25. Qc2 Rd7 { Lanka,Z-Pribyl,J/ Germany 1996/GER-chT/ 1/2-1/2 (38) } 