1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. Bc4 Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. a4 c6 8. Re1 a5 { From structural perspective, this looks like a safer plan. Black prevents his opponent from gaining too much space on the queenside, keeps the b6 square available for the queen in order to counter-attack the b2-pawn, and gets ready to trade in the center. Usually Black continues with exd4 followed by Nc5 and Be6, trying to exchange the light-squared bishop. } *
