1. d4 d6 2. e4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. Bc4 Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. a4 a5 8. Re1 c6 9. h3 h6 10. Be3 Re8 { [%csl Ge7,Re4,Gd4][%cal Ge5d4,Ge7f8,Ge8e4,Rd6d5,Gd4e5] } 11. d5 { A rare plan. White doesn't want to keep the tension in the centre.Do not forget to keep an eye on the d5-square, no matter which line you would choose. Right now Black could have solved his problems with } ( 11. Ba2 { was tried } 11... Qc7 12. Nh4 Nf8 13. Qf3 exd4 14. Bxd4 Ne6 15. Bxe6 Bxe6 16. Nf5 Bxf5 17. Qxf5 Nd7 { and Black equalised, S. Zhigalko-Yudin, Dubai rapid 2014. } ) ( 11. Qd2 { is also more popular. } ) 11... Nb6 $1 { [%csl Rd5][%cal Rb6d5,Rf6d5,Rb6c4] } ( 11... Nf8 $14 { [%cal Gf8g6] The first new move by Andreikin. A logical idea: Black wants to transfer his N to the kingside. Unfortunately this wasn't a good plan, because Black's queenside becomes very weak. } 12. Nd2 $1 { Kasimdzhanov immediately starts a great plan. He prepares for Bf1 followed by Nc4. } 12... Ng6 13. Bf1 $1 { [%cal Gd2c4] A good prophylactic move. White frees the c4-square for his knight. } 13... Rb8 $6 ( 13... cxd5 { was tougher } 14. exd5 { [%csl Rg6,Rf6,Rf7,Rg7][%cal Rf7f6,Rg7g6] } 14... Nh4 15. Bb5 Rf8 16. Nc4 $36 { [%cal Ge3b6,Gc4b6] and White has a wonderful initiative on the queenside. } ) 14. Ba7 ( 14. Nc4 $1 { after a repetition. } ) 14... Ra8 15. Be3 Rb8 16. Nc4 $16 { After repetition of moves Kasimdzhanov continues his main plan. Black's situation is very difficult. 1-0 (36) White wins. } ) 12. Bb3 ( 12. Nd2 $5 ) 12... cxd5 13. Bxb6 Qxb6 14. Nxd5 Nxd5 15. Qxd5 Be6 16. Qd3 Rac8 { should be equalizing, Tseitlin-Shirazi, Bagneux 1994. } *
