1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. Bc4 Be7 { [%cal Gd7b6,Ge1g1] } 6. a4 $5 { A modern move order which intends to take out the sting of the early Nd7-b6 ideas. } ( { More common is } 6. O-O O-O 7. Re1 c6 { [%cal Gb7b5] } 8. a4 a5 { [%csl Gc5,Gb6] } ) 6... O-O { [%cal Ge1h1] } 7. O-O ( 7. a5 c6 { [%cal Ga8b8,Gb7b6] } ) 7... c6 8. Re1 a5 { From structural perspective, this looks like a safer plan. Black prevents his opponent from gaining too much space on the queenside, keeps the b6 square available for the queen in order to counter-attack the b2-pawn, and gets ready to trade in the center. } 9. Ba2 { [%csl Ra2] One of the possible plans, which however has the drawback of committing the bishop prematurely. } 9... exd4 { The main idea for the second player is to prepare the trade of his light-squared bishop with Bc8-e6. } 10. Nxd4 ( 10. Qxd4 { changes nothing regarding the planning } 10... Nc5 { [%cal Gc8e6] } 11. Bf4 Be6 $1 12. e5 dxe5 13. Qxe5 Nfd7 ( 13... Re8 $1 14. Bxe6 Nxe6 15. Bd2 Qb6 $15 { [%csl Ge8][%cal Ga8d8,Gd8d1,Ge7d6,Gf6g4] } ) 14. Qe3 Bxa2 $6 ( 14... Re8 $1 ) 15. Qxe7 $1 Qxe7 16. Rxe7 Be6 17. Nd4 $14 { Bauer,C (2644) -Bressac, S (2379) Cannes 2018 } ) 10... Nc5 { [%cal Gc5e4,Gc8e6,Gc5a4,Gd8b6,Gb6b2] } 11. Qe2 ( { The bishop development } 11. Bg5 { [%csl Rb2][%cal Gc1g5] leaves the b2- pawn unprotected and can be used with } 11... Qb6 12. Qd2 { [%csl Rb2,Rd4][%cal Gd2c3,Rb6b2,Rb6d4] True, Black does not threaten to gain the pawn at once, but is constantly annoying his opponent with his active queen. } 12... Bd7 ( 12... Qxb2 $4 13. Reb1 Qa3 ( 13... Qxc3 $1 14. Qxc3 Nfxe4 15. Qa3 Bxg5 $16 ) 14. Bxf7+ ) ( { An interesting tactical possibility, worth knowing is revealed in the line } 12... h6 $5 13. Bf4 ( { Here is the tactic } 13. Bxh6 $5 gxh6 14. Qxh6 Nd3 $3 { [%cal Rb6d4] } 15. cxd3 ( 15. Re3 Nxf2 $1 { [%csl Gg4][%cal Gc5d3,Gd3f2,Gf2g4] } 16. Rg3+ N6g4 $1 { [%csl Gh3,Rd4][%cal Gf2h3,Gb6d4] } ( 16... N2g4 $4 17. Qg6+ Kh8 18. Rh3+ ) ) 15... Qxd4 { [%csl Rg7,Rh7][%cal Rd4e5,Re5g7,Rf6h7] } 16. Qg5+ Kh8 17. Qh4+ { [%csl Ge7][%cal Gh4e7,Gf6h7,Gd4g7] } ) 13... Be6 { [%csl Rf4] Now the bishop is standing on the road of our pieces. } 14. Nxe6 Nxe6 15. Be3 ( 15. Bxe6 fxe6 16. Bxd6 $2 ( 16. e5 dxe5 ( 16... Ng4 17. Nd1 dxe5 18. Bxe5 $2 ( 18. Bg3 Bc5 $13 ) 18... Rad8 19. Qe2 Nxf2 $1 ) 17. Bxe5 Rad8 { [%csl Rf2][%cal Gd8d1,Gf8f2,Gb6f2] } 18. Qe2 Nd7 19. Bg3 Nc5 $44 ) 16... Ng4 $1 { [%csl Rf2] } 17. Nd1 ( 17. Bxe7 Rxf2 { [%cal Rf2f1,Rb6f2] } ) 17... Nxf2 $1 18. Nxf2 Bxd6 19. Qxd6 Qxf2+ ( 19... Rxf2 20. Qxe6+ Kh8 $17 ) 20. Kh1 Rf6 $17 ( 20... Qf6 $17 ) ) 15... Qb4 $13 { [%csl Rb2,Re4,Ra4][%cal Rb4a4] } ) 13. f3 Rad8 14. Be3 Rfe8 15. Qf2 Qxb2 16. Nce2 Qb6 17. Nb3 Be6 18. Nxc5 dxc5 19. Bxe6 fxe6 20. Nf4 Bf8 21. Nd3 Nd7 $44 { Bartel,M (2653) -Can, E (2557) Gjakova 2016 } ) ( 11. h3 { [%csl Gf2][%cal Gh2h3,Gf6g4,Gg4f2,Gh3g4] Stops the knight maneuver, and can be met with } 11... Qb6 { Main move. } ( { But here is a case for the immediate } 11... Be6 $5 { [%csl Gd4][%cal Ga3a2] } 12. Qf3 ( 12. Nxe6 fxe6 { [%cal Gd6d5] } 13. Be3 d5 { [%csl Ra2] } 14. e5 Nfd7 { This is already very pleasant for Black. } 15. f4 Na6 ( { Better was } 15... Qe8 $15 { [%cal Ge8g6,Ge8e6] } ) ( { Or } 15... g5 $1 { [%csl Ra2] making use of the fact that the light-squared bishop is out of the game. } ) 16. Qg4 Rf5 17. Ne2 $2 ( 17. Nxd5 $3 cxd5 18. Bxd5 { [%cal Gd5e6] } 18... exd5 19. Qxf5 $16 ) 17... h5 18. Qf3 Nxe5 19. Qf1 Ng6 $17 20. Ng3 Rf7 21. Nxh5 e5 22. c3 Nxf4 23. Bxf4 exf4 24. Bb1 Bc5+ 25. Kh1 Qg5 26. Qf3 Be3 27. Bc2 Nc5 28. g3 fxg3 29. Bh7+ Kf8 30. Qxe3 g2+ 31. Kg1 Rf1+ 32. Kh2 g1 33. Qxg1 Qxg1# { 0-1 (33) Yu,Y (2675) -Yudin,S (2546) Dubai 2014 } ) 12... Qd7 ( 12... Nfd7 { [%csl Ge6][%cal Gf7e6,Gf8f2,Gd7e5] } 13. Be3 Ne5 { [%csl Gf3] } 14. Qe2 Bxa2 15. Rxa2 g6 16. Raa1 Re8 17. b3 Bf8 $13 { [%csl Ge8][%cal Gf8g7] Movsesian,S (2672) -Yudin,S (2546) Dubai 2014 } ) 13. Be3 Bxa2 14. Rxa2 Rfe8 15. Raa1 Bd8 { [%csl Re4,Rd6] } 16. Bf4 Ne6 17. Rad1 Nxf4 18. Qxf4 g6 19. Nf3 Be7 20. e5 Nh5 21. Qh6 f5 22. exd6 Bxd6 23. Rxe8+ Rxe8 24. Qd2 Rd8 25. Qd4 Ng7 26. Qb6 Qc7 27. Qb3+ Qf7 28. Qb6 Qc7 29. Qb3+ Qf7 30. Qb6 Qc7 { 1/2-1/2 (30) Gopal,G (2580) -Kuzubov,Y (2661) Doha 2014 } ) ) ( { If } 11. Qf3 { [%csl Rd4] } 11... Qb6 { [%csl Ra4][%cal Rc5a4,Rb6d4,Gc1g5] hits the white knight and once again White has to be careful. } 12. Bg5 ( 12. Nb3 Nxb3 13. Bxb3 Be6 14. Be3 Qc7 ( 14... Qb4 $13 15. Bxe6 fxe6 16. Qh3 e5 17. Qe6+ Rf7 { [%cal Ge7d8,Gd8b6] } 18. Bd2 ( 18. Bg5 Qxb2 ) 18... Qb6 { [%cal Gb6f2] } ) 15. Ba2 ( { Or } 15. Bxe6 $5 fxe6 16. Qh3 e5 17. Qe6+ Kh8 18. Qb3 $11 ) 15... Bxa2 16. Rxa2 Nd7 17. Qe2 Bf6 $13 ) 12... Be6 ( 12... Kh8 $5 { [%cal Gb6b2,Gg8h8,Ga1b1] } 13. e5 $6 ( 13. Rab1 ) 13... dxe5 14. Rxe5 Bg4 15. Qf4 Ne6 16. Nxe6 fxe6 $17 { [%csl Rf2,Rf4][%cal Gf8f2,Re7d6] } ) ( 12... Qxb2 $4 13. Rab1 Qa3 14. Nd5 $1 { [%cal Rd5e7] } 14... Qxf3 15. Nxe7+ ) ( 12... Qb4 $5 { [%csl Rb2,Rd4,Ra4][%cal Gg8h8,Gb6b4,Rb4d4,Rb4a4] } 13. Nf5 ( 13. Rad1 $4 Bg4 { [%csl Rd1,Rf3] } ) 13... Bxf5 14. exf5 ( 14. Qxf5 { [%csl Rb2] } 14... Qxb2 $17 { [%cal Rf3c3] } ) 14... Rfe8 $17 { [%csl Re7,Ra2][%cal Rd6d5] } ) 13. Nxe6 Nxe6 14. Qe3 ( 14. Bxe6 fxe6 15. Qh3 e5 { [%csl Rf2][%cal Gf8f7,Ga8f8] } ) 14... Qxe3 $6 ( 14... Nc5 $1 15. Rab1 $6 ( 15. h3 $1 Rfe8 $13 ( 15... Rae8 ) ) 15... Ng4 $1 16. Qf4 Bxg5 17. Qxg5 ( 17. Qxg4 Bf6 $1 18. Ne2 ( 18. Qe2 Qb4 $19 ) 18... Qb4 ) 17... Nxf2 $1 18. Kf1 Rae8 $1 19. Qh4 Re6 $1 20. Kxf2 Nxe4+ 21. Kf1 Nd2# ) 15. Bxe3 Ng4 16. Bd2 $14 Bh4 17. g3 Bf6 18. Kg2 Nc5 19. Bc4 Rfe8 20. f3 Ne5 21. Be2 Ned7 22. b3 Ne6 23. Rac1 Nd4 24. Bf1 Ne5 25. Re3 Ne6 26. Ne2 d5 $2 ( 26... Bd8 $1 { [%cal Gd8b6] } 27. Nf4 Bb6 28. Ree1 Nd4 29. Be2 f5 $1 ) 27. exd5 cxd5 28. Bc3 $16 { Carlsen,M (2786) -Radjabov,T (2751) Cap d'Agde 2008 } ) ( 11. Bf4 { [%csl Rb2][%cal Gf4g5] is similar to Bc1-g5 from above, after } 11... Qb6 { [%csl Gf4][%cal Ge4e5] } 12. Qd2 ( 12. e5 dxe5 13. Bxe5 Bg4 14. Qd2 { [%cal Ga8d8,Gd2f4] } 14... Ncd7 { [%cal Gd7f6,Ge7f6,Gd7e5] } ( 14... Rad8 $6 15. Qf4 $1 ) ) 12... Be6 $1 ( 12... Re8 13. h3 Bd7 14. e5 $1 dxe5 15. Bxe5 Qb4 ( 15... h6 16. Re3 Nh7 17. Rae1 Bg5 18. f4 Bh4 19. Rf1 $16 { Paravyan,D (2469) -Goganov,A (2609) Sochi 2015 } ) 16. Qg5 $40 ( 16. Re3 Nh5 17. Qe2 g6 18. g4 Bf6 19. Bxf6 Nxf6 20. Rd1 Rxe3 21. Qxe3 Rf8 $4 ( 21... Nxa4 $13 ) 22. Qe5 Ne8 23. Nb3 Nxb3 24. Rxd7 Qc5 25. Qf4 g5 26. Qf3 Nd4 27. Qd3 { 1-0 (27) Berg,E (2593) -Hamdouchi,H (2576) Calvia 2007 } ) ) 13. Nxe6 ( 13. Be3 Qb4 $13 { [%cal Gb4d4,Gb4a4] } ) 13... fxe6 ( 13... Nxe6 14. Bxe6 fxe6 15. e5 dxe5 16. Bxe5 Ng4 17. Qd4 Qb4 $13 ) 14. e5 dxe5 15. Bxe5 Kh8 $13 { [%csl Rf2,Ra2][%cal Gf6d5,Rf8f2] } ) ( 11. f3 { [%csl Re4][%cal Gf2f3] just weakend White } 11... Qb6 { [%cal Gb6g1] } 12. Kh1 Re8 13. Nb3 Nfd7 $13 ( 13... Be6 ) ( 13... Na6 $5 { [%csl Rb3,Ra2][%cal Ra2b3,Ga6b4] } ) ) ( { And we know that } 11. Nf5 $6 { is dubious as long as the pawns are doubled, and the white light-squared bishop locked after } 11... Bxf5 12. exf5 d5 { [%csl Ra2] } ) 11... Qb6 12. Rd1 Be6 13. Nxe6 fxe6 { [%cal Gb6f2,Gf8f2] } 14. Be3 d5 $13 { [%csl Ra2,Gd5][%cal Ge6d5] Black achieved the desired d6-d5 advance and has no problems at all. } 15. f4 Qa6 16. e5 Qxe2 17. Nxe2 Ng4 18. Bd4 h5 19. c4 Rac8 20. g3 Nh6 21. Kg2 Rfd8 22. cxd5 cxd5 23. b3 Nf5 24. Bg1 Rc6 25. Rac1 Rdc8 26. Kf3 Ne4 27. Rxc6 Rxc6 28. Bb1 Nc3 29. Nxc3 Rxc3+ 30. Ke2 g6 31. Bd3 Bc5 32. Bxc5 Rxc5 33. Rb1 Kf7 34. Kd2 Rc7 35. b4 axb4 36. Rxb4 Ne7 37. Rb6 Nc8 38. Rb1 Ne7 39. h3 Nf5 40. g4 hxg4 41. hxg4 Nh6 42. Rh1 Kg7 43. Rg1 Kf7 44. Ke3 Rc3 45. Rb1 Rc7 46. Kd4 Nxg4 47. Rh1 Kf8 48. Rh8+ Kg7 49. Re8 Kf7 50. Rh8 Kg7 51. Re8 { 1/2-1/2 The game is a draw. } 1/2-1/2
