1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. Bc4 Be7 6. O-O ( 6. a4 { White can "prevent" Black's plan with this move and transpose into a normal classical Philidor. } 6... Nb6 $6 { does not make much sense since White can put his bishop on the ideal a2-square and gain an important tempo. } 7. Ba2 $14 ) 6... Nb6 7. Bd3 { Let us cast a glance over two rare moves: } ( 7. dxe5 Nxc4 8. exf6 Bxf6 9. Nd5 O-O 10. Nxf6+ Qxf6 11. Qd4 Ne5 12. Nxe5 Qxe5 13. Qxe5 dxe5 { 1/2-1/2 Valsecchi,A (2422) -Popovic,D (2507) Plovdiv 2015 } ) ( 7. Bb5+ c6 8. dxe5 dxe5 9. Qxd8+ Bxd8 10. Bd3 { Varas,C (2293) -Cuenca Jimenez,J (2473) Linares 2014 } 10... Bc7 ) 7... Nfd7 { This looks artificial. Black delays the exchange on d4. However, it is unclear to me what advantage that should bring him. With natural development White appears to have at least the more pleasant game. } 8. Re1 ( 8. a4 a5 9. Be3 O-O ( 9... c6 10. Re1 ( 10. Ne2 { Played with the idea of 9.c3. Black should react by capturing on d4. } 10... exd4 11. Bxd4 c5 ( 11... O-O 12. Ng3 Bf6 13. c3 Ne5 14. Nxe5 dxe5 15. Be3 Be6 16. Qe2 Bg5 17. Bc5 Be7 18. Be3 Bg5 19. Bc5 Be7 20. Be3 Bg5 { 1/2-1/2 Nemeth,M (2454) -Markus,R (2605) Nagykanizsa 2013 } ) 12. Bxg7 Rg8 13. Bc3 c4 14. Ng3 cxd3 15. Qxd3 Nc5 16. Qe3 Nbxa4 17. Bd4 Nb6 18. Qh6 Rg6 19. Qxh7 { Sulypa,A (2483) -Moranda,W (2572) Polanica Zdroj 2013 } 19... Ne6 $1 { and it is not clear whether White has enough compensation for the material disadvantage. } ) 10... O-O 11. h3 ( 11. Bf1 $1 { leads by transposition of moves to the same position as in Smirin-Markus. } ) 11... exd4 12. Bxd4 Bf6 13. Bf1 Re8 14. b3 Ne5 15. Nxe5 dxe5 16. Be3 Nd7 17. Qf3 Qe7 18. Rad1 Nc5 { Vega Gutierrez,B (2180) -Strikovic,A (2529) Las Palmas 2013 } ) 10. Re1 ( 10. dxe5 $5 dxe5 11. Bxb6 cxb6 ( 11... Nxb6 12. Nxe5 Bf6 13. Nc4 $14 ) 12. Nd5 Bd6 13. Qe2 Nf6 14. Bc4 Nxd5 15. Bxd5 $14 { Starostits,I (2470) -Popovic, D (2562) La Roda 2013 } ) 10... exd4 11. Nxd4 Nc5 12. Bf1 Bd7 13. b3 Re8 14. Qd2 Bf6 15. f3 $14 { Palac,M (2569) -Marjanovic,D (2330) Sarajevo 2014 } ) ( 8. Ne2 exd4 $1 9. Nexd4 O-O 10. Re1 Bf6 11. c3 Re8 12. Bc2 a5 13. a4 Nc5 { Kantans,T (2412) -Popovic,D (2547) Aschach 2013 } ) 8... O-O 9. Bf1 ( 9. Be3 c6 10. h3 Re8 11. a4 a5 12. Bf1 Bf8 ( 12... exd4 13. Qxd4 { results in more or less the same sort of position as in Smirin-Markus. } ) 13. d5 $1 Nf6 14. Ra3 $1 cxd5 15. exd5 Bd7 16. Bxb6 $1 Qxb6 17. Rb3 Qc7 18. Nd2 Bf5 19. Nc4 Nd7 20. Nb5 Qb8 21. g4 Bg6 22. h4 $40 { Guseinov,G (2628) -Markus,R (2619) Al-Ain 2012 } ) 9... c6 10. a4 a5 11. Be3 exd4 12. Qxd4 Nc5 13. Rad1 Re8 14. h3 Bf8 15. b3 $14 { White has reached a more pleasant position by playing natural moves. In what follows, he would like to attack the backward pawn on d6. } 15... h6 16. Qd2 Nbd7 17. Bf4 Qf6 18. Bg3 Ne5 19. Nd4 g5 { Black has warded off White's threats very well, but with this move he weakens his kingside. } 20. Re3 { White goes for the wrong plan. } ( 20. f3 $14 ) 20... h5 $1 21. Bxe5 dxe5 22. Rf3 { This was White's idea. } 22... Qg6 $6 ( 22... Qd8 $1 23. Bc4 Be6 24. Nxe6 Qxd2 25. Rxd2 fxe6 ) 23. Bc4 Ne6 ( 23... Re7 24. Nf5 Rd7 25. Qe3 Rxd1+ 26. Nxd1 Be6 27. Rg3 f6 28. Nb2 $16 ) 24. Nxe6 Bxe6 25. Bxe6 fxe6 26. Ne2 ( 26. Rg3 $1 g4 27. Qe3 Rad8 28. hxg4 h4 29. Rf3 $16 ) 26... Be7 ( 26... Bb4 $1 ) 27. Qc3 g4 28. Rfd3 Qxe4 29. Ng3 Qg6 30. hxg4 h4 31. Nh5 Qxg4 32. Qxe5 Rad8 33. Kh2 ( 33. Nf6+ Bxf6 34. Qxf6 Rd5 35. Rd4 Qg5 36. Qxg5+ Rxg5 37. Rxh4 $16 ) 33... Rxd3 34. Rxd3 Rf8 35. Rd4 Qg6 36. Qe2 $6 ( 36. Rf4 $14 ) 36... Rf5 37. g4 hxg3+ 38. Nxg3 Rf7 $6 ( 38... Rd5 39. Rg4 Rg5 ) 39. Rg4 $2 ( 39. Kg2 $14 ) 39... Rxf2+ $1 40. Kh3 Rxe2 41. Rxg6+ Kf7 42. Nxe2 Kxg6 43. Kg4 Bd6 44. Kf3 Kf5 45. Ke3 Be5 $15 { 1/2-1/2 The game is a draw. } 1/2-1/2
