1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. Bc4 Be7 6. O-O Nb6 7. Bb3 { A natural square, but here the bishop is susceptible to attacks by a knight on e5. } 7... exd4 { Now, however, White should recapture with the queen. } 8. Qxd4 ( 8. Nxd4 { allows erlaubt } 8... c5 { and no matter where the white knight goes, 9...c4 or 10...c4 will follow and White must exchange his lovely bishop for the black knight on b6. However, things are not so clear-cut. } 9. Nf5 $1 ( 9. Nde2 c4 10. Ba4+ Nxa4 11. Nxa4 Nxe4 12. Qd4 Nf6 13. Qxc4 O-O 14. Nac3 Be6 15. Qd3 Rc8 { Zherebukh,Y (2629) -Bauer,C (2638) Haguenau 2013 } ) 9... Bxf5 10. exf5 c4 ( 10... d5 $13 ) 11. Ba4+ Nxa4 12. Nxa4 O-O 13. Nc3 d5 14. Be3 Bb4 ( 14... Qd7 ) 15. Bd4 Bxc3 16. bxc3 ( 16. Bxc3 Ne4 ) 16... Re8 { White has a strong bishop but a worse structure; therefore, the position should be dynamic equality. } ) 8... O-O 9. a4 a5 10. h3 Nfd7 $1 { The knight is aiming for c5, so as to attack the bishop on b3. In addition, the f6-square will be made available to the bishop. This is one of the basic positions after 7.Bb3. White has tested several moves here. } 11. Be3 { The best square for the bishop. Here it puts pressure on the black knight which will appear on c5 and also on the knight on b6. } ( 11. Rd1 $5 Nc5 ( 11... Bf6 12. Qe3 Qe7 13. Qe1 Nc5 14. Be3 Bxc3 15. Qxc3 Nxe4 16. Qd3 Nc5 17. Bxc5 dxc5 18. Re1 $44 ) 12. Ba2 Bd7 13. e5 Ncxa4 14. exd6 cxd6 15. Be3 ( 15. Nxa4 Nxa4 16. Ne5 dxe5 17. Qxd7 Nc5 18. Qg4 $44 ) 15... Nxc3 16. Qxc3 Na4 17. Qa3 b5 18. Bd4 ( 18. Bd5 $44 ) 18... Bc6 19. Qe3 Bf6 20. Nh2 $2 ( 20. Rab1 $44 ) 20... Nxb2 $17 { Petkov,V (2484) -Paunovic,D (2532) Figueira da Foz 2008 } ) ( 11. Bf4 Bf6 12. Qd2 Nc5 13. Rfe1 Re8 ( 13... Be6 { immediately also looks good. } ) 14. Rad1 Be6 ( 14... Bxc3 15. Qxc3 Nbxa4 ( 15... Nxe4 $2 16. Bxf7+ $1 Kxf7 17. Rxe4 $36 ) 16. Bxa4 Nxa4 17. Qa3 $44 ) 15. Bxe6 Nxe6 16. e5 Nc4 17. Qc1 Nxf4 18. exf6 Qxf6 { Anton,T (2380) -Strikovic, A (2564) Obrenovac 2011 } ) ( 11. Nd5 $6 { The position transformation after this move favors Black. The pressure is relieved and the bishop on b3 is shut in. } 11... Nxd5 12. exd5 Nc5 13. Bc4 ( 13. Qd1 ) 13... Bd7 14. Bb5 Bf6 15. Qd1 Bxb5 16. axb5 Qe8 $15 { Souleidis,G (2420) -Zaragatski,I (2488) Hamburg 2014 } ) ( 11. Re1 Bf6 12. Qd1 Nc5 13. Be3 Nxb3 14. cxb3 Nd7 15. Qc2 b6 16. Nd5 { 1/2-1/2 Arngrimsson,D (2396) -Strikovic,A (2523) Belgrad 2009 } 16... Bb7 $1 17. Qxc7 Bxd5 18. Qxd8 Rfxd8 19. exd5 Bxb2 ) 11... Nc5 ( 11... Bf6 { first is also possible. } 12. Qd1 ( 12. Qd2 Nc5 13. Ba2 $5 ( 13. Nd4 Re8 14. f3 Nxb3 15. cxb3 d5 ) 13... Nbxa4 14. Nxa4 Nxa4 15. c3 $44 ) 12... Nc5 13. Bxc5 dxc5 14. e5 Qxd1 15. Raxd1 Be7 ) 12. Qd1 { White allows his structure to be weakened but insists on more space and semi-open files to exert pressure on Black's position. } ( 12. Qd2 { should be more accurate than 12.Qd1, but without changing the basic evaluation in any way. } 12... Nxb3 13. cxb3 Nd7 ( 13... c6 14. Rad1 f5 $5 ( 14... Nd7 15. Qc1 $13 ( 15. Bf4 Nc5 ) ) 15. e5 d5 16. Qc1 c5 ( 16... Nd7 $13 ) 17. Nb5 d4 18. Bxd4 cxd4 19. Rxd4 Qe8 20. Nc7 Qg6 21. Nxa8 Nxa8 $13 ) 14. Nd5 ( 14. Qc2 { leads by transposition of moves to Baklan-Strikovic. führt mit Zugumstellung zu Baklan-Strikovic. } ) 14... Nc5 15. Qc2 b6 16. b4 $6 ( 16. Nd4 ) 16... axb4 17. Nxb4 Qe8 $13 { Olazagoitia Rodriguez,J (2190) -Argandona Riveiro,I (2382) Bergara 2010 } ) ( 12. Rad1 Nxb3 13. cxb3 Be6 14. Nd5 Nxd5 15. exd5 { Gundavaa,B (2501) -Caruana,F (2791) Blitz-WM Dubai 2014. } 15... c5 $1 ) ( 12. Ba2 $5 { is an interesting new move, with the idea - similar to the game above Petkov-Paunovic - of giving up a pawn for the initiative, e.g. } 12... Bd7 ( 12... Bf6 $2 13. e5 $16 ) ( 12... Be6 13. Bxe6 Nxe6 14. Qd3 Nd7 { is the safer choice for Black. } ) 13. e5 Ncxa4 14. Nd5 Nxd5 15. Bxd5 Nc5 16. Qc4 Be6 17. Bxc5 b5 $1 18. Qxb5 Bxd5 19. exd6 Bxd6 20. Bxd6 Qxd6 21. Rfd1 c6 22. Qd3 ) 12... Nxb3 13. cxb3 Nd7 ( 13... c6 $5 { Black would like to follow up with ...f5 so as to create a superiority in the centre. } 14. Re1 Nd7 ( 14... f5 $2 15. exf5 { and Black cannot take on f5, because that would be followed by Bxb6 and then Rxe7. } ) 15. Nd2 $6 ( 15. Qc2 ) 15... f5 $1 16. exf5 Rxf5 17. Nf3 { Brenjo,S (2516) -Damljanovic,B (2536) Vrnjacka Banja 2013 } 17... Ne5 18. Nxe5 Rxe5 ) 14. Qc2 Ne5 $6 { The opening of the d-file gives White the initiative. } ( 14... b6 15. Nd5 Nc5 { and Black should have no problems. } ) 15. Nxe5 dxe5 16. Rad1 ( 16. Rfd1 Bd6 17. Nb5 $36 { seems to be even stronger. } ) 16... Bd6 17. f4 { This looks tempting, but it concedes the advantage. } ( 17. Nb5 $14 ) 17... exf4 18. Bxf4 Ra6 $1 19. Kh1 ( 19. e5 Bc5+ 20. Kh2 Qe8 ) 19... Qh4 20. Bxd6 cxd6 ( 20... Rxd6 21. Rxd6 cxd6 ) 21. Qd3 Be6 22. Nb5 Qe7 $6 { There was no need to give up the pawn. } ( 22... Rd8 23. Nc7 Rb6 24. Nd5 Ra6 25. Qb5 Raa8 26. Nf4 { with a mini-initiative for White. } ) 23. Nxd6 h6 ( 23... Bxb3 24. Qxb3 Rxd6 25. Rxd6 Qxd6 26. Qxb7 $14 ) 24. Nf5 Bxf5 25. Rxf5 ( 25. exf5 $14 ) 25... Re8 26. Qd5 Qxe4 27. Qxf7+ Kh7 28. Rf4 Qe2 29. Rg1 Rg6 30. Qxb7 Qxb2 31. Qd5 Re3 ( 31... Re5 $13 ) 32. Rf3 Re1 33. Rf8 Rxg1+ 34. Kxg1 Qc1+ 35. Rf1 Qe3+ 36. Kh1 Rg5 37. Qf3 Re5 38. Qd1 Qc3 39. Qb1+ Kg8 40. Rd1 Re8 41. Qg6 Rb8 42. Rd3 Qe5 43. Qg3 Qe8 $2 ( 43... Qxg3 44. Rxg3 Kf7 { and Black should be able to hold the rook ending. } ) 44. Rd5 $16 Ra8 45. Qc7 Kh7 46. Rd7 Qg6 47. Rd6 $2 ( 47. Qe5 $16 ) 47... Qb1+ 48. Kh2 Qxb3 49. Rd7 Qb2 50. Qf4 Ra6 $4 { blunders away the point. } ( 50... Kh8 ) 51. Qe4+ Rg6 ( 51... Kh8 52. Rd8# ) 52. Rd6 { 1-0 White wins. } 1-0
